'''California High-Speed Rail''' ('''CAHSR''') is a publicly-funded [[high-speed rail]] system under construction across [[California]] by the [[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]. The project was authorized by a [[2008 California Proposition 1A|2008 statewide ballot]], and is being constructed in two major phases. Phase&nbsp;1, which is about {{convert|494|mi|km}} long, will connect the Bay Area and the Greater Los Angeles Area through the Central Valley communities. Upon completion, Phase 1 is required to provide a non-stop express connection between San Francisco and Los Angeles in two hours and 40&nbsp;minutes. Phase&nbsp;2 would extend the system north to [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]] and south to [[San Diego]], for a total system length of {{convert|776|mi|km}}. With a top speed of {{convert|220|mph|abbr=on}}, CAHSR trains would be the fastest in the U.S.{{efn|The [[Acela]], with a top speed of {{convert|160|mph}}, is currently the fastest rail service in the U.S.}} and among the fastest in the world.{{efn|The [[Fuxing (train)|Fuxing series]] in China, with a top speed of {{convert|350|km/h|mph}}, is currently the fastest rail service in the world in terms of operating speed.}}

The Initial Operating Segment (IOS), a section of Phase&nbsp;1 in the Central Valley that spans 35&nbsp;percent of its total length, is the first segment that has advanced to construction, and will connect communities from [[Merced, California|Merced]] to [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]], at a cost of $36.7&nbsp;billion. Revenue service on the IOS is projected to commence in 2032.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |title=2025 Supplemental Project Update Report |url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/2025-Project-Update-Report-SUP-FINAL-081925-A11Y.pdf |website=hsr.ca.gov}}</ref>

Construction began in the Central Valley in 2015, and as of August 2025, a total of $13.8&nbsp;billion had been spent on the project.<ref name=":0" /> Other major expenditures include upgrades to existing rail lines in the [[San Francisco Bay Area]] and [[Greater Los Angeles]], where Phase&nbsp;1 is planned to share tracks with conventional passenger trains. Regulatory clearance has been obtained for the full route connecting San Francisco and Los Angeles. However, the [[California High-Speed Rail Authority]] ("the Authority") has not yet received sufficient funding commitment to construct the full buildout of the Phase&nbsp;1 system, currently estimated at $89–$128&nbsp;billion. As of August 2025, the Authority's interim goal is to connect the Bay Area to the IOS via a connection at [[Gilroy, California|Gilroy]], which is {{convert|70|mi|km}} south of San Francisco, to either [[Bakersfield, California|Bakersfield]] or [[Palmdale, California|Palmdale]], by the year 2038. The estimated cost to build the San Francisco–Bakersfield system is $54 billion, and the estimate for the San Francisco–Palmdale system is $84 billion.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{Cite web |title=Supplemental Project Update Report Provides a Path Forward to Delivering the First-in-the-Nation System |url=https://hsr.ca.gov/2025/08/22/news-release-delivering-high-speed-rail-for-californians-supplemental-project-update-report-provides-a-path-forward-to-delivering-the-first-in-the-nation-system/ |access-date=2025-10-07 |website=hsr.ca.gov}}</ref> The extension to Palmdale will connect the project to the Southland via the Metrolink system, while the Burbank-Los Angeles-Anaheim segment is constructed to complete the Phase I system. 

The project has been politically controversial. Supporters state that it would alleviate [[California housing shortage|housing shortages]], [[Air traffic flow management|air traffic]] and [[Traffic congestion|highway congestion]], reduce [[pollution]] and [[greenhouse gas]] emissions, and provide economic benefits by linking the state's inland regions to coastal cities.<ref name="SPUR 2022">{{cite web |last1=Nutt-Beers |first1=Jackson |last2=Tolkoff |first2=Laura |date=May 19, 2022 |title=How Cities Can Make the Most of California's High-Speed Rail Investment |url=https://www.spur.org/news/2022-05-19/how-cities-can-make-most-californias-high-speed-rail-investment |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240315175657/https://www.spur.org/news/2022-05-19/how-cities-can-make-most-californias-high-speed-rail-investment |archive-date=March 15, 2024 |access-date=March 15, 2024 |publisher=SPUR}}</ref> Opponents argue that the project is too expensive in principle, has lost control of cost and schedule, and that the budgetary commitment precludes other transportation or infrastructure projects in the state. The route choice has been controversial, along with the decision to construct the first high-speed segment in the Central Valley rather than in more heavily populated parts of the state. The project has experienced significant delays and cost overruns caused by management issues, legal challenges and permitting hold-ups, and inefficiencies from inadequate and sporadic funding. The Authority has also faced notable delays in securing agreements to relocate utilities, such as power lines and water infrastructure.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-02-21 |title=California watchdog says high-speed rail on track to blow more deadlines |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2025/02/21/california-high-speed-rail-ig-report-00205506 |access-date=2025-10-14 |website=POLITICO |language=en}}</ref> A state-appointed high-speed rail peer review group confirmed that the project may fall short of promises made to voters in several areas, including ridership and travel times.<ref name=slow />

== Background ==
{{Main|History of California High-Speed Rail}}

=== Legislative context ===

High-speed rail in California was first proposed in 1979 by Governor [[Jerry Brown]].<ref name="Cowan 2022">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/03/16/us/california-bullet-train.html|title=Two Former Governors Weigh In on California's Bullet Train|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=March 16, 2022|last=Cowan|first=Jill|access-date=March 10, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240310173721/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/03/16/us/california-bullet-train.html|archive-date=March 10, 2024}}</ref> In 1982, Brown signed a bill authorizing $1.25&nbsp;billion in bonds for a high-speed rail line between Los Angeles and San Diego.<ref name="TRR"/> The law failed due to concerns over its economic viability, environmental impact, and [[Caltrans]]' objection to the handling of the project by a private company.<ref name="TRR">{{cite journal |url=https://onlinepubs.trb.org/Onlinepubs/trr/1987/1143/1143-006.pdf |title=High-Speed Rail in California: The Dream, the Process, and the Reality |last1=Smith |first1=George C. |last2=Shirley |first2=Earl |journal=Transportation Research Record |pages=36–43 |access-date=April 4, 2024 |archive-date=April 10, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240410224202/https://onlinepubs.trb.org/Onlinepubs/trr/1987/1143/1143-006.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> In 1993, the state created the [[California Intercity High-Speed Rail Commission]].<ref name="SB1420"/> In 1996, the California Legislature and Governor [[Pete Wilson]] passed the High-Speed Rail Act, which formed the California High-Speed Rail Authority to plan, design, construct and operate a statewide high-speed rail system.<ref name="SB1420">{{cite web|url=http://leginfo.ca.gov/pub/95-96/bill/sen/sb_1401-1450/sb_1420_bill_960924_chaptered.html|title=Bill Number: SB 1420|publisher=California Legislative Information|access-date=March 10, 2024|archive-date=March 10, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240310173721/http://leginfo.ca.gov/pub/95-96/bill/sen/sb_1401-1450/sb_1420_bill_960924_chaptered.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2008, Governor [[Arnold Schwarzenegger]] championed [[2008 California Proposition 1A|Proposition 1A]] (Prop&nbsp;1A), which authorized $9&nbsp;billion in bonds to begin the planning and construction of high-speed rail and a further $950&nbsp;million to upgrade [[commuter rail]] systems in Northern and Southern California that would connect with the high-speed rail system. Prop&nbsp;1A, which passed with about 53&nbsp;percent of the vote, set several requirements for the high-speed rail system, including that the nonstop travel time from the [[Salesforce Transit Center]] (formerly: [[San Francisco Transbay Terminal]]) in San Francisco to [[Los Angeles Union Station]] in Los Angeles should be no more than two hours and 40&nbsp;minutes.<ref name="Prop 1A Ballotpedia">{{cite web |title=California Proposition 1A, High-Speed Rail Bond Measure (2008) |url=https://ballotpedia.org/California_Proposition_1A,_High-Speed_Rail_Bond_Measure_(2008) |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314103740/https://ballotpedia.org/California_Proposition_1A,_High-Speed_Rail_Bond_Measure_(2008) |archive-date=March 14, 2024 |access-date=March 10, 2024 |publisher=[[Ballotpedia]]}}</ref><ref name="Prop 1A text"/> 

After the prioritized funding of the San Francisco to Los Angeles section, Prop 1A proposed additional potential corridors for high-speed rail investment:
*Oakland–San Jose
*Sacramento–Merced
*Los Angeles–Inland Empire
*Inland Empire–San Diego
*Los Angeles–Irvine
The only specific route requirements set by Prop&nbsp;1A were to complete a link between San Francisco and Los Angeles, and that the Authority would study the additional corridors for possible inclusion. It did not require that all corridors be built, indicate the order of construction, or specify precise routes and station locations other than in San Francisco and Los Angeles.<ref name="Prop 1A text">{{cite web|url=https://www.lalawlibrary.org/pdfs/PROP_1108_1A.pdf|title=Text of Proposed Law: Proposition 1A|publisher=LA Law Library|access-date=March 10, 2024|archive-date=March 10, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240310173721/https://www.lalawlibrary.org/pdfs/PROP_1108_1A.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> The designation of the San Francisco to Los Angeles segment as "Phase 1," and additional adopted corridors as "Phase 2," was published in the Authority's 2012 Business Plan.<ref>{{Cite web |title=2012 Business Plan |url=https://hsr.ca.gov/communications-outreach/reports/business-plans/2012-business-plan/ |access-date=2026-02-05 |website=hsr.ca.gov}}</ref>

=== Statewide objectives ===

The planned high-speed rail system would reduce travel times between the northern and southern parts of the state. Driving or taking an intercity bus between San Francisco and Los Angeles takes six to eight hours. Since the ''[[Coast Daylight]]'' was discontinued in 1974, there has been no direct rail connection between San Francisco and Los Angeles, with the closest [[Amtrak]] service now in [[Oakland–Jack London Square station|Oakland]]. The Amtrak ''[[Coast Starlight]]'', the only direct rail service from Oakland to Los Angeles, takes eleven hours and runs once daily.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.railpassengers.org/site/assets/files/20928/coast-starlight.pdf|title=Amtrak's Coast Starlight|publisher=Rail Passengers Association|access-date=March 15, 2024|archive-date=March 30, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240330063105/https://railpassengers.org/site/assets/files/20928/coast-starlight.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> While the ''[[Gold Runner]]'' takes about nine hours, a bus transfer is required for part of the route.<ref name="San Joaquins timetable">{{cite web|url=https://amtrak-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/JPA17915_TimetableEdits_September_V2.pdf|title=San Joaquins Timetable|publisher=Amtrak|access-date=March 15, 2024|archive-date=March 15, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240315175656/https://amtrak-bucket.s3.us-west-1.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/JPA17915_TimetableEdits_September_V2.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> High-speed rail is intended to be competitive with air travel; while the actual station-to-station time would be slower than flying, reduced waiting and boarding times and fewer security checks would make total travel times competitive, with other potential benefits including passenger comfort and greater reliability.<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Sauter-Servaes |first1=Thomas |last2=Krautscheid |first2=Thomas |last3=Schober |first3=Alexander |title=A Level Playing Field for Comparing Air and Rail Travel Times |journal=The Open Transportation Journal |date=2019 |volume=13 |pages=48–56 |url=https://opentransportationjournal.com/VOLUME/13/PAGE/48/FULLTEXT/#:~:text=Research%20on%20the%20interaction%20between,than%20air%20travel%20%5B27%5D. |language=en |doi=10.2174/1874447801913010048 |doi-access=free|hdl=11475/17340 |hdl-access=free }}</ref> The entry of high speed rail into the transportation market typically results in improved on-time flight performance, service quality, and price competition.<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Fang |first=Hanming |date=March 2025 |title=Competition and Quality: Evidence from High-Speed Railways and Airlines |url=https://direct.mit.edu/rest/article-abstract/107/2/494/114755/Competition-and-Quality-Evidence-from-High-Speed?redirectedFrom=fulltext# |journal=The Review of Economics and Statistics |volume=107 |issue=2 |pages=494–509 |doi=10.1162/rest_a_01294 |via=MIT Press Direct|url-access=subscription }}</ref> High-speed rail in California would reduce flight congestion on one of the busiest domestic air routes in the US, with the SF-LA short haul air routes averaging 132&nbsp;scheduled flights daily.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2016/07/05/americans-fly-lax-sfo-more-than-any-other-flight-path-in-the-u-s/|title=Americans fly LAX-SFO more than any other flight path in the U.S|work=[[The Mercury News]]|date=July 5, 2016|access-date=March 15, 2024|archive-date=March 15, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240315184645/https://www.mercurynews.com/2016/07/05/americans-fly-lax-sfo-more-than-any-other-flight-path-in-the-u-s/|url-status=live}}</ref>

The high-speed rail system may relieve housing pressure in major urban areas, especially the Bay Area, by providing access to cheaper housing in the Central Valley, which would be particularly beneficial for business travelers and hybrid [[remote work]]ers who commute only a few times a week. While the rail project may incentivize denser housing and job growth around stations, with cities such as Fresno and Bakersfield planning for major real estate investments in their downtowns,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article280898638.html|title=Fresno has big hopes for high-speed rail to spur downtown renaissance. What's the grand plan?|work=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=October 24, 2023|last=Sheehan|first=Tim|access-date=March 15, 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bakersfieldcity.us/291/High-Speed-Rail-Station-Area-Plan-Goals|title=High-Speed Rail Station Area Plan Goals|publisher=City of Bakersfield|access-date=March 15, 2024|archive-date=March 15, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240315175657/https://www.bakersfieldcity.us/291/High-Speed-Rail-Station-Area-Plan-Goals|url-status=live}}</ref> the urban policy advocacy group [[SPUR (San Francisco organization)|SPUR]] noted the risk of [[urban sprawl]] as a result of increased housing demand in the Central Valley, and that the state should consider mitigating this in its planning approach.<ref name="SPUR 2022"/> Phase&nbsp;1 of high-speed rail is projected to reduce annual statewide CO<sub>2</sub> emissions by about 600,000&nbsp;tons by replacing highway trips and flights; however, it would only account for 0.2&nbsp;percent of the state's total emissions from all sectors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ocregister.com/2024/02/24/new-figures-show-that-california-high-speed-rail-wont-do-much-about-climate-change/|title=New figures show that California High-Speed Rail won't do much about climate change|work=[[The Orange County Register]]|last=Joffe|first=Marc|date=February 24, 2024|access-date=March 15, 2024|archive-date=March 15, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240315175656/https://www.ocregister.com/2024/02/24/new-figures-show-that-california-high-speed-rail-wont-do-much-about-climate-change/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2023, [[Caltrans]] issued the 2023 California State Rail Plan, which is a comprehensive plan to upgrade and modernize the state's intercity passenger and freight rail systems through 2050. Provisions of the plan include increasing the capacity of existing railways, establishing new services, improving service frequencies and train speeds, and integrating ticketing between transit agencies in order for ticketing through all rail systems to be able to be done statewide. The plan outlines the integration of high-speed rail into the statewide system as its primary north-south passenger link. Although the Authority has not indicated completion dates for the full system, the 2023 version of the state rail plan used 2050 for the completion of both Phase&nbsp;1 and Phase&nbsp;2.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://dot.ca.gov/-/media/dot-media/programs/rail-mass-transportation/documents/california-state-rail-plan/20230309-casrp-public-dor-guidance.pdf|title=California State Rail Plan 2023|publisher=California Department of Transportation|year=2023|access-date=April 29, 2024}}</ref>

== Plans, construction and project status ==

{{main|Construction of California High-Speed Rail}}

The project is split into two major phases: Phase&nbsp;1 is to connect San Francisco to Los Angeles via the [[Central Valley, California|Central Valley]]; Phase&nbsp;2 is an extension of Phase&nbsp;1 both to the north from Merced to Sacramento and to the south from Los Angeles to San Diego via the [[Inland Empire]]. As of 2024, the Authority is targeting completion of the "Initial Operating Segment" (IOS), a {{convert|171|mi|km|adj=on}} section within the Phase&nbsp;1 route in the Central Valley, with {{convert|119|mi|km}} under active construction. The project has received approximately $23&nbsp;billion in combined state and federal funding through the end of 2024 (including a disputed $3.3 billion of federal funding), and has spent a total of $13.8&nbsp;billion. As of February 2024, the entire Phase&nbsp;1 was projected to cost between $89–128&nbsp;billion, with allowance for future inflation.<ref name="2024 Business Plan">{{cite web |title=2024 Draft Business Plan |url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/2024-Draft-Business-Plan-020724-A11Y.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313030820/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2024/02/2024-Draft-Business-Plan-020724-A11Y.pdf |archive-date=March 13, 2024 |access-date=March 12, 2024 |publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]}}</ref>
=== Phase&nbsp;1 ===

[[Image:CAHSR_map.svg|thumb|300px|High-speed rail project status as of May 2025]]

Phase&nbsp;1 of the planned route, about {{convert|494|mi|km}} long,<ref name="2024 Business Plan"/> runs from the Salesforce Transit Center in San Francisco to the [[Anaheim Regional Transportation Intermodal Center]] in Anaheim, with intermediate stops planned for [[Millbrae station|Millbrae]], [[San Jose Diridon station|San Jose]], [[Gilroy station|Gilroy]], [[Merced station (California High-Speed Rail)|Merced]], [[Madera station (California High-Speed Rail)|Madera]], [[Fresno station (California High-Speed Rail)|Fresno]], [[Kings–Tulare Regional Station|Kings/Tulare (Hanford)]], [[Bakersfield station (California High-Speed Rail)|Bakersfield]], [[Palmdale Transportation Center|Palmdale]], [[Burbank Airport station (California High-Speed Rail)|Burbank]] and Los Angeles.<ref name="Statewide map"/> An additional station between Los Angeles and Anaheim, at [[Norwalk/Santa Fe Springs station|Norwalk]] or [[Fullerton Transportation Center|Fullerton]], is being considered.<ref name="Los Angeles to Anaheim section">{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/project-sections/los-angeles-to-anaheim/|title=Los Angeles to Anaheim|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=January 25, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240125222842/https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/project-sections/los-angeles-to-anaheim/|url-status=live}}</ref> The existing [[San Francisco 4th and King Street station|4th and King Caltrain station]] in San Francisco is expected to be the northern terminus of Phase&nbsp;1 until the future completion of the Downtown Rail Extension (now known as [[The Portal (San Francisco)|The Portal]]) to the Salesforce Transit Center.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/station-communities/san-francisco/|title=San Francisco station|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=January 26, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240126015038/https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/station-communities/san-francisco/|url-status=live}}</ref>

From San Francisco, the planned route runs south to Gilroy before crossing the [[Diablo Range]] eastward over [[Pacheco Pass]] into the Central Valley. The route branches north to Merced via a [[Flying junction|flying]] [[Wye (rail)|wye]] which is intended to serve as the connection for a future Phase&nbsp;2 extension to Sacramento.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/project-sections/merced-to-fresno/merced-to-fresno-central-valley-wye/|title=Merced to Fresno – Central Valley Wye|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030449/https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/project-sections/merced-to-fresno/merced-to-fresno-central-valley-wye/|url-status=live}}</ref> As part of Phase&nbsp;1, Merced is planned to serve as a transfer point to the ''Gold Runner'' and [[Altamont Corridor Express]]{{efn|ACE plans to expand operations to Merced by 2030.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mantecabulletin.com/news/local-news/ace-working-toward-rail-service-in-26-to-downtown/|title=ACE working toward rail service in '26 to downtown|work=[[Manteca Bulletin]]|last=Wyatt|first=Dennis|date=July 28, 2023|access-date=April 4, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030451/https://www.mantecabulletin.com/news/local-news/ace-working-toward-rail-service-in-26-to-downtown/|url-status=live}}</ref>}} (ACE) trains continuing towards Stockton, Sacramento and other destinations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/station-communities/merced/|title=Merced station|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=January 26, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240126015722/https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/station-communities/merced/|url-status=live}}</ref> As of the 2025 Supplemental Project Update, the Authority is considering delaying construction of the Merced extension in order to prioritize an earlier connection to the Bay Area through Gilroy.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Baig |first=Yousef |date=2025-08-22 |title=For California high-speed rail to succeed, part of the Central Valley will have to wait {{!}} Opinion |url=https://calmatters.org/commentary/2025/08/california-high-speed-rail-strategy/ |access-date=2025-10-06 |work=CalMatters |language=en-US}}</ref> South of there, Madera through Bakersfield stations are located along the main line in the Central Valley.<ref name="Statewide map"/> From Bakersfield, the high-speed rail route crosses the [[Tehachapi Mountains]] via the [[Tehachapi Pass]] to Palmdale in the [[Mojave Desert]]. It then tunnels under the [[San Gabriel Mountains]] to reach Los Angeles and Anaheim.<ref name="Statewide map">{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/newsroom/maps/Statewide_topo.pdf|title=Proposed Statewide Alignment|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|date=September 2020|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030453/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/newsroom/maps/Statewide_topo.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref>

In the urbanized areas from San Francisco to Gilroy and from Burbank to Anaheim, the Phase&nbsp;1 route follows existing railroad right-of-ways. In 2012, the Authority adopted a "blended" approach to construction in these segments, which would involve high-speed trains sharing track with Amtrak and local commuter trains, specifically [[Caltrain]] in the Bay Area and [[Metrolink (California)|Metrolink]] in Southern California.<ref name="2012 Business Plan"/> This approach was adopted to reduce costs and mitigate the impact of construction on surrounding communities, but also limits train speed in these sections to a maximum of {{convert|110|mph}}.<ref name="2012 Business Plan">{{cite web|url=https://www.hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/about/business_plans/BPlan_2012_rpt.pdf|title=California High-Speed Rail Program Revised 2012 Business Plan|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|date=April 2012|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030453/https://www.hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/about/business_plans/BPlan_2012_rpt.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> Between Gilroy and Burbank, the planned route will run on dedicated high-speed tracks.<ref name="2012 Business Plan"/>

==== Initial Operating Segment (IOS) ====

The Authority is advancing work in sections, first targeting full completion of a {{conv|171|mi|km|adj=on}} "Initial Operating Segment" (IOS).  Within this segment, {{conv|119|mi|km}} are under active construction.

The IOS is intended to begin carrying passengers along a limited portion of the route before the full Phase 1 is completed. This initial service would span either from Merced or Madera, to Fresno and Hanford, and then to Bakersfield. High-speed trains would fully replace existing, slower Amtrak ''Gold Runner'' service south of Merced to Bakersfield.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cdn.sjjpa.com/wp-content/uploads/DRAFT-2023-SJJPA-Business-Plan-Update_Public-Review-Draft.pdf|title=Draft 2023 Business Plan Update|publisher=San Joaquin Joint Powers Authority|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=November 4, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231104180918/https://cdn.sjjpa.com/wp-content/uploads/DRAFT-2023-SJJPA-Business-Plan-Update_Public-Review-Draft.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> ''Gold Runner'' passengers continuing to Southern California currently transfer to [[Amtrak Thruway]] buses at Bakersfield.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amtrak.com/san-joaquins-train|title=San Joaquins|publisher=Amtrak|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=August 2, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802062718/https://www.amtrak.com/san-joaquins-train|url-status=live}}</ref> This bus connection will remain necessary until the construction of Phase 1 reaches Palmdale, where the high speed rail station will be integrated with the existing Metrolink transportation hub.<ref name="2023 Project Update Report"/>

As of April 2026, the IOS construction progress includes {{conv|80|mi|km}}, or 67%, of contiguous guideway declared complete and ready for track-laying, as well as 58 civil construction structures completed, 30 underway, and 4 not started yet.<ref>{{Cite web |title=BuildHSR: High-Speed Rail Projects |url=https://www.buildhsr.com/ |access-date=2026-04-05 |website=BuildHSR California}}</ref>  The remainder of the planned {{conv|119|mi|km}} is expected to complete civil construction by the end of 2026. {{conv|54|mi|km}} of extensions to Merced and to Bakersfield, which would complete the IOS, are under engineering design.<ref name="chsra cv status report 2024 nov">{{cite web |title=Central Valley Status Report, November 2024 |url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/CVSR-2024-10-Data-2024-08-Draft-3-A11Y.pdf |website=hsr.ca.gov |publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]] |access-date=8 January 2025}}</ref>

