The scope of the IOS has changed several times in the project's history. In 2012 it was planned to run from Merced through Bakersfield to Burbank (just north of Los Angeles), a distance of about {{convert|300|mi|km}}. This would have closed a major gap in California intercity rail services, as the existing ''Gold Runner'' terminates at Bakersfield and does not continue on to Los Angeles.<ref name="2012 Business Plan"/> In 2016, due to changes in funding and financing plans,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/about/legislative_affairs/SB1029_Project_Update_Report_050119.pdf|title=Project Update Report to the California State Legislature|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|date=May 2019|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030451/https://www.hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/about/legislative_affairs/SB1029_Project_Update_Report_050119.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> the Authority changed the IOS to a northern segment between San Jose and Bakersfield, the "Silicon Valley to Central Valley line".<ref name="2016 Business Plan">{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/about/business_plans/2016_BusinessPlan.pdf|title=Connecting and Transforming California: 2016 Business Plan|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|date=May 1, 2016|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030454/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/about/business_plans/2016_BusinessPlan.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2019 [[Gavin Newsom]] chose the current definition of an IOS between Merced and Bakersfield in the Central Valley,<ref>{{cite news |author1=Jill Cowan |title=Trump Administration to Pull $4 Billion in Funding for California High-Speed Rail |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2025/06/04/us/politics/california-high-speed-rail-funding.html?searchResultPosition=3 |access-date=23 July 2025 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=4 June 2025 |quote=In 2019, Gov. Gavin Newsom announced that the state would instead first open a kind of starter segment of the train connecting two smaller cities in California’s agricultural Central Valley}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=Jill Cowan |title=How High-Speed Rail Got Caught Between Newsom and Trump |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/20/us/california-today-high-speed-rail-newsom-trump.html |access-date=23 July 2025 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=20 February 2019 |quote=he announced, the project would be scaled back for the time being, instead stretching from Bakersfield to Merced}}</ref>  a {{convert|171|mi|km|adj=mid}} long segment with {{convert|119|mi|km}} under active construction.<ref name="2023 Project Update Report">{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/2023-Project-Update-Report-FINAL-022823.pdf|title=2023 Project Update Report|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=February 16, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240216093925/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/2023-Project-Update-Report-FINAL-022823.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> If additional funding becomes available, the Authority still intends to construct the northern Bay Area connection before the southern connection to Los Angeles.<ref name="2024 Business Plan"/>

Construction on the IOS began with a groundbreaking in Fresno on January 6, 2015, with construction of the first vertical structure, [[Fresno River Viaduct]], beginning on June 16, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/jan/07/california-breaks-ground-high-speed-rail-project|title=California breaks ground on high-speed rail project but completion not assured|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Carroll|first=Rory|date=January 7, 2015|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030448/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2015/jan/07/california-breaks-ground-high-speed-rail-project|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media |date=2015-06-22 |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=akXU7vgk1dg |title=Construction of Fresno River Viaduct Underway - June 18, 2015 |format=video |publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]] |access-date=2025-11-14 |via=YouTube}}</ref> The first 119 miles, stretching from [[Madera, California|Madera]] south to [[Shafter, California|Shafter]], a city about {{convert|20|mi|km}} northwest of Bakersfield, are being constructed under four [[design-build]] contracts titled "construction packages".<ref name="construction packages"/> These include constructing the [[railroad grade]], viaducts, road overpasses and underpasses and other structures along the route, but not the track itself.<ref name="construction packages">{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/business-opportunities/contract-opportunities/design-build-construction-packages/|title=Design-Build Construction Packages|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030448/https://hsr.ca.gov/business-opportunities/contract-opportunities/design-build-construction-packages/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bowden |first1=Bridgit |last2=Johnson |first2=Shawn |date=October 30, 2019 |title=The High-Speed Rail Debate Persists In California |url=https://www.wpr.org/derailed/high-speed-rail-debate-persists-california |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191105083718/https://www.wpr.org/derailed/high-speed-rail-debate-persists-california |archive-date=November 5, 2019 |access-date=March 18, 2024 |work=[[National Public Radio]] |language=en |quote=the rail authority agreed to build Dejong an underpass}}</ref> In August 2022, the Authority approved design contracts for the remaining {{convert|52|mi|km}} of the IOS connecting Madera to Merced and Shafter to Bakersfield,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/2022/08/17/news-release-california-high-speed-rail-board-approves-design-contracts-to-prepare-for-construction-into-merced-and-bakersfield/|title=News Release: California High-Speed Rail Board Approves Design Contracts to Prepare for Construction into Merced and Bakersfield|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|date=August 17, 2022|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=December 9, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231209173748/https://hsr.ca.gov/2022/08/17/news-release-california-high-speed-rail-board-approves-design-contracts-to-prepare-for-construction-into-merced-and-bakersfield/|url-status=live}}</ref> with construction contracts expected in 2025–2026.<ref name="2024 Business Plan"/>

In October 2022, the Authority approved a design contract for the Merced, Fresno, Kings/Tulare and Bakersfield stations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/2022/10/20/news-release-california-high-speed-rail-board-awards-design-contract-for-central-valley-stations/|title=California High-Speed Rail Board Awards Design Contract for Central Valley Stations|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|date=October 20, 2022|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=September 29, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230929101647/https://hsr.ca.gov/2022/10/20/news-release-california-high-speed-rail-board-awards-design-contract-for-central-valley-stations/|url-status=live}}</ref> Planning for the Madera station is occurring under a separate agreement with the [[San Joaquin Joint Powers Authority]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cdn.sjjpa.com/wp-content/uploads/20231122140306/Madera-HSR-Station-Full-Build_NOP_2023-11-22_FINAL.pdf|title=Notice of Preparation of an Environmental Impact Report: Madera High Speed Rail (HSR) Station Full-Build Project (Phase 3)|publisher=San Joaquin Joint Powers Authority|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030453/https://cdn.sjjpa.com/wp-content/uploads/20231122140306/Madera-HSR-Station-Full-Build_NOP_2023-11-22_FINAL.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> The construction contract for track and electrical power systems on the IOS<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/business-opportunities/contract-opportunities/track-systems/|title=Track & Systems|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030449/https://hsr.ca.gov/business-opportunities/contract-opportunities/track-systems/|url-status=live}}</ref> is expected in 2024–2025.<ref name="2024 Business Plan"/>  As of February 2024, Construction Packages 1–3 were more than 70&nbsp;percent complete and Construction Package 4 was at 98&nbsp;percent.<ref name="2024 Business Plan"/> The full Merced–Bakersfield line was expected to be complete in 2029.<ref name="2023 Project Update Report"/>

By 2025, Authority plans were for the IOS to be completed in 2031; the Inspector General, however, determined the IOS (including Merced and Bakersfield extensions) was unlikely to be operational by 2033. The Authority is planning to begin passenger revenue service on the active construction segment (Madera to N. Bakersfield) in 2032.<ref>{{cite web |author1=Benjamin M. Belnap |title=Merced to Bakersfield Segment The Authority Is Unlikely to Complete the Segment as Currently Envisioned within Its Planned Schedule |url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/Schedule-Engagement-Report-FINAL-A11Y.pdf |publisher=HSR.CA.gov |access-date=2 April 2025 |date=3 February 2025 |quote=the latest project information, the 2030 target date has been pushed back to 2031 [...] staying within the 2033 schedule envelope is unlikely}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author1=ALEX NIEVES |title=California watchdog says high-speed rail on track to blow more deadlines |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2025/02/21/california-high-speed-rail-ig-report-00205506 |access-date=2 April 2025 |work=[[Politico]] |date=21 February 2025 |quote=the initial 171-mile Central Valley line is unlikely to be completed by the High-Speed Rail Authority's 2033 timeline}}</ref><ref name="2025 CHSRA supplemental PUR" />

==== Blended corridor investments ====

[[Image:Caltrain Stadler KISS in San Jose 2023 dllu.jpg|thumb|[[Stadler KISS]] electric trainset operated by Caltrain after electrification]]
[[Image:Link Union Station diagram.png|thumb|A diagram of the Link US project in Los Angeles Union Station, showing the location of planned high-speed rail platforms.]]

Concurrently with Central Valley construction, the Authority has worked with other California transportation agencies and rail operators to prepare the northern and southern blended segments for high-speed rail operations. In the Bay Area, the [[Caltrain Modernization Program|electrification of Caltrain]] will enable electric high-speed trains to run on the existing Caltrain commuter rail corridor from San Francisco to San Jose. Work began in 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.caltrain.com/media/21596/|title=Caltrain Electrification Frequently Asked Questions|publisher=Caltrain|date=September 2021|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030448/https://www.caltrain.com/media/21596/|url-status=live}}</ref> and was completed in September 2024.<ref>{{Cite web |last=DiNapoli |first=Alyse |date=2024-09-21 |title=Caltrain goes fully electric |url=https://www.smdailyjournal.com/news/local/caltrain-goes-fully-electric/article_5e2c23a2-77c4-11ef-8610-47587c0ec09b.html |access-date=2024-10-05 |website=San Mateo Daily Journal |language=en}}</ref>

The corridor from San Jose to Gilroy will also require electrification;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/project-sections/san-jose-to-merced/|title=San José to Merced|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=March 30, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240330055800/https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/project-sections/san-jose-to-merced/|url-status=live}}</ref> as of February 2024, the Authority was still in negotiations with [[Union Pacific Railroad]] over proposed alterations to the tracks.<ref name="2024 Business Plan"/> Several [[grade separation]]s and passing tracks have been completed or are planned along the route from San Francisco to Gilroy, in order to improve track capacity, speed and safety for blended Caltrain/high-speed rail operations.<ref name="2024 Business Plan"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/news/2023/11/24/caltrain-plans-for-4-track-segments-complicate-palo-altos-effort-to-redesign-rail-crossings/|title=Caltrain plans for 4-track segments complicate Palo Alto's effort to redesign rail crossings|work=Palo Alto Online|date=November 24, 2023|last=Sheyner|first=Gennady|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030448/https://www.paloaltoonline.com/news/2023/11/24/caltrain-plans-for-4-track-segments-complicate-palo-altos-effort-to-redesign-rail-crossings/|url-status=live}}</ref> Since many [[Level crossing|at-grade crossings]] will remain,{{efn|For example, 49 from San Mateo to Palo Alto<ref>{{cite news |title=Palo Alto, Calif., wants grade separation for high-speed rail project, but authority is not listening |url=https://www.rtands.com/grade-crossings/palo-alto-calif-wants-grade-separation-for-high-speed-rail-project-but-authority-is-not-listening/ |access-date=April 2, 2024 |work=[[Railway Track & Structures]] |date=August 4, 2022 |quote=A new report has revealed that 41 out of 49 at-grade crossings between San Mateo and Palo Alto [...] |issn=0033-9016 |archive-date=April 2, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240402175049/https://www.rtands.com/grade-crossings/palo-alto-calif-wants-grade-separation-for-high-speed-rail-project-but-authority-is-not-listening/ |url-status=live }}</ref> and 29 from San Jose to Gilroy.<ref name=SJtoGilroy />}} other safety improvements such as [[Four-quadrant gate|quad gates]] are being considered.<ref name=SJtoGilroy>{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/At-Grade-Crossing-Safety-1-26-2022_a11y.pdf|title=At-Grade Crossing Safety|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=January 5, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240105201832/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2022/02/At-Grade-Crossing-Safety-1-26-2022_a11y.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref>

In Southern California, the Link US project plans to reconfigure Los Angeles Union Station from a [[Train station#Terminus|terminal]] to a run-through station and add two dedicated high-speed rail platforms.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/station-communities/los-angeles/|title=Los Angeles|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=January 26, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240126021755/https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/station-communities/los-angeles/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metro.net/projects/link-us/|title=Link Union Station (Link US)|work=LA Metro |publisher=Los Angeles County Metropolitan Transportation Agency|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=January 7, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170107004847/https://www.metro.net/projects/link-us/|url-status=live}}</ref> The shared Amtrak and Metrolink tracks from Burbank to Anaheim will require electrification. Between Los Angeles and [[Fullerton, California|Fullerton]], the rail corridor is also heavily used by [[BNSF Railway|BNSF]] freight trains coming from the Ports of [[Port of Los Angeles|Los Angeles]] and [[Port of Long Beach|Long Beach]], requiring further separation to prevent congestion.<ref name="Los Angeles to Anaheim section"/><ref name="LA Anaheim Update Nov 2023">{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/LA-A-SAA-and-PA-Overview-NovBoard-A11Y.pdf|title=Los Angeles to Anaheim Update|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|date=November 2, 2023|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=January 5, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240105211420/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/LA-A-SAA-and-PA-Overview-NovBoard-A11Y.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> As of November 2023, the Authority proposed to build a fourth track on the existing three-track corridor, with two electrified tracks to be used for passenger trains (including high-speed rail) and two non-electrified tracks for freight, in addition to grade separations and crossing safety improvements.<ref name="LA Anaheim Update Nov 2023"/><ref name="Slaten 2023">{{cite news|url=https://www.ocregister.com/2023/11/01/california-high-speed-rail-authority-considering-adding-new-track-in-southern-california-corridor/|title=4th track proposed for LA-to-Anaheim segment of planned high-speed rail|work=[[The Orange County Register]]|last=Slaten|first=Michael|date=November 1, 2023|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030449/https://www.ocregister.com/2023/11/01/california-high-speed-rail-authority-considering-adding-new-track-in-southern-california-corridor/|url-status=live}}</ref> Some freight trains may be allowed to use the passenger tracks during off-peak hours.<ref name="LA Anaheim Update Nov 2023"/>

The Authority has also funded other projects such as the installation of [[positive train control]] systems along the shared commuter rail lines, and upgrades to existing stations and railyards to accommodate both future high-speed rail and other passenger rail services.<ref name="Connectivity and Bookend Investments">{{cite web|url=https://www.hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/communication/info_center/factsheets/Connectivity_Bookends.pdf|title=Connectivity and Bookend Investments|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=February 15, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220215051326/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/communication/info_center/factsheets/Connectivity_Bookends.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== Remainder of Phase&nbsp;1 ====

Construction of the remaining Phase&nbsp;1 route is still on hold due to budget constraints. As of June 2024, the [[environmental impact statement]]s for {{convert|463|mi|km}} of the {{convert|494|mi|km|adj=on}} route had been certified,<ref>{{Cite web |last=CAHSRA |title=California High-Speed Rail Authority Board Clears Final Environmental Milestone to Connect Downtown San Francisco to Downtown Los Angeles |url=https://hsr.ca.gov/2024/06/27/news-release-california-high-speed-rail-authority-board-clears-final-environmental-milestone-to-connect-downtown-san-francisco-to-downtown-los-angeles/}}</ref> which specifies the alignment from San Francisco to Los Angeles and clears it for detailed engineering design and construction. The remaining segment to be certified is the Los Angeles–Anaheim section.

The Merced to San Jose section would cross the Pacheco Pass roughly along the route of [[California State Route 152|SR&nbsp;152]].<ref name="2024 Business Plan"/> It would include [[Pacheco Pass Tunnels|several tunnels]], the longest of which would be {{convert|13.5|mi|km}}, making it the longest intercity rail tunnel in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Pacheco-Pass-Factsheet-for-web-English.pdf|title=Tunneling in Northern California: San Jose to Merced Project Section Factsheet|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 21, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240321100123/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2021/09/Pacheco-Pass-Factsheet-for-web-English.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> Engineering challenges along this section include "poor-quality rock formations, faults and shear zones, and potentially high groundwater inflows that can affect tunnel stability."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.enr.com/articles/54030-california-high-speed-rail-connection-to-silicon-valley-approved|title=California High-Speed Rail Connection to Silicon Valley Approved|last=Aragon|first=Greg|date=April 29, 2022|work=Engineering News-Record|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030449/https://www.enr.com/articles/54030-california-high-speed-rail-connection-to-silicon-valley-approved|url-status=live}}</ref> The Authority expects to start design work on this section in 2024, and begin pre-construction work such as land acquisition in about 2026–2028, funds permitting.<ref name="2023 Project Update Report"/>

[[Image:Tehachapi_Loop_Aerial.jpg|thumb|Part of Phase&nbsp;1 will travel through the Tehachapi Pass, which is currently traversed by the Union Pacific Railroad. Tehachapi Loop shown here.]]
The Bakersfield–Palmdale section of the line will cross Tehachapi Pass, roughly parallelling the Union Pacific Railroad's [[Mojave Subdivision]]. Due to its heavy freight traffic and sharp curves (including the famous [[Tehachapi Loop]]), there is no current passenger service through the pass.<ref name="Bakersfield to Palmdale Draft EIR/EIS"/> While the proposed high-speed rail alignment will not include any long tunnels comparable to those in Pacheco Pass, it has nine shorter tunnels and several viaducts more than {{convert|200|ft|m}} high.<ref name="Bakersfield to Palmdale">{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/newsroom/maps/Bakersfield_to_Palmdale.pdf|title=Bakersfield to Palmdale Project Section|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|date=December 2021|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=January 26, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240126075741/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/newsroom/maps/Bakersfield_to_Palmdale.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> The maximum [[Grade (slope)|grade]] through the pass would be 2.8&nbsp;percent, making it the steepest portion of the Phase&nbsp;1 route.<ref name="Bakersfield to Palmdale Draft EIR/EIS">{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/programs/bakersfield-palmdale/BP_Draft_EIRS_Vol_1_CH_2_Alternatives.pdf|title=Bakersfield to Palmdale Project Section Draft Project EIR/EIS|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|date=February 2020|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030451/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/programs/bakersfield-palmdale/BP_Draft_EIRS_Vol_1_CH_2_Alternatives.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> At a press conference in January 2025 in [[Kern County, California|Kern County]], state and CHSRA leaders reiterated the importance of this section and promoted the vision of a combined CAHSR-[[High Desert Corridor]]-[[Brightline West]] rail corridor.<ref name="sf chronicle cp4 railhead groundbreaking">{{cite web |last1=Swan |first1=Rachel |date=January 6, 2025 |title=California's new plan for its long-delayed high speed rail system: Connect it to Las Vegas |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/california/article/ca-high-speed-rail-las-vegas-20018173.php |access-date=January 7, 2025 |work=San Francisco Chronicle |publisher=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]}}</ref>

From Palmdale to Burbank the proposed route crosses the San Gabriel Mountains on an alignment roughly along [[California State Route 14|SR&nbsp;14]].{{efn|Several different options are still being studied for the route, but the Authority has identified the "SR14A" route along State Route 14 as its preferred option.<ref name="Palmdale to Burbank fact sheet 2022"/>}} It would require the most tunneling of any of the mountain crossings, with four separate tunnels totaling {{convert|28|mi|km}} in length.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/newsroom/maps/Palmdale_to_Burbank.pdf|title=Palmdale to Burbank Project Section Map|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|date=October 2020|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=February 17, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240217122546/https://www.hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/newsroom/maps/Palmdale_to_Burbank.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="Palmdale to Burbank fact sheet 2022">{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/2022-0805-P-B_DEIRS_Fact-Sheet_4pgs_English_Rem.pdf|title=Palmdale to Burbank Project Section: Connecting Community Update 2022|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=January 31, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240131202501/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/2022-0805-P-B_DEIRS_Fact-Sheet_4pgs_English_Rem.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> One of the major challenges along this section is the crossing of the [[San Andreas Fault]] and several parallel, smaller fault zones, where a large earthquake could significantly deform the tracks. To compensate for this, the rail beds and tunnel diameters will be constructed wider at fault crossings to allow for any needed track realignment in the future. The tracks will cross the San Andreas Fault itself above ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/PB_02.0-AppxD_P2K_PEPD_RECORD_SET_Rev02_Design_Baseline_Report-a11y.pdf|title=Palmdale to Burbank Project Section: Draft Environmental Impact Report/Environmental Impact Statement|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|date=August 2022|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=January 31, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240131203506/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2022/08/PB_02.0-AppxD_P2K_PEPD_RECORD_SET_Rev02_Design_Baseline_Report-a11y.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref>

In total, the southern extension from Bakersfield to Los Angeles may require {{Convert|36|mi|km}} of tunnels. In 2018, the Authority estimated that the tunneling may cost $26–$45&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|last=Vartabedian|first=Ralph|title=Cost for California bullet train system rises to $77.3 billion|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-bullet-train-cost-increase-20180309-story.html|access-date=March 10, 2018|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=March 9, 2018|quote=Among the most challenging is the cost of about 36 miles of tunnels through mountainous Southern California, which could range anywhere from $26 billion to $45 billion, according to the report|archive-date=March 15, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240315213019/https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-bullet-train-cost-increase-20180309-story.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== Operations infrastructure ====

The high-speed rail system is planned to run entirely on renewable energy.<ref name="CAHSRA sustainability"/> Due to the large energy demand of high-speed trains, the system is being planned to generate much of its own power.<ref name="Ohnsman 2023"/> Solar arrays and battery backup systems are to be installed at traction power substations along the route; however, they will still be tied into the California power grid, allowing them to share energy as needed. The Authority plans to install solar panels capable of producing 44&nbsp;[[megawatt]]s, and batteries to store 124&nbsp;[[megawatt hour]]s.<ref name="CAHSRA sustainability"/> The on-site generation of solar power is estimated to cut future electricity costs by 75&nbsp;percent compared to purchasing it from the state grid,<ref name="CAHSRA sustainability">{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/programs/green-practices-sustainability/sustainability/|title=Sustainability|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=February 9, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240209125205/https://www.hsr.ca.gov/programs/green-practices-sustainability/sustainability/|url-status=live}}</ref> and will keep the system operational if the grid suffers a blackout.<ref name="Ohnsman 2023">{{cite news|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanohnsman/2023/06/12/californias-100-billion-electric-bullet-train-will-be-fully-solar-powered/|title=California's $100 Billion Electric Bullet Train Will Be Fully Solar Powered|work=[[Forbes]]|last=Ohnsman|first=Alan|date=June 12, 2023|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030448/https://www.forbes.com/sites/alanohnsman/2023/06/12/californias-100-billion-electric-bullet-train-will-be-fully-solar-powered/|url-status=live}}</ref>{{better source needed|reason=[[WP:FORBESCON]]|date=May 2024}}

There are plans for a heavy maintenance facility, serving as the location for major train inspections and repairs, in the Central Valley. It will also serve to receive and test high-speed trainsets along the IOS track currently being constructed.<ref name="2012 DEIR service">{{cite web|url=https://railroads.dot.gov/sites/fra.dot.gov/files/fra_net/2429/2_C_Operations_and_Service_Plan_Summary.pdf|title=Appendix 2-C, Operations and Service Plan|work=California High-Speed Train Project Revised DEIR/Supplemental DEIS|year=2012|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=January 6, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240106110716/https://railroads.dot.gov/sites/fra.dot.gov/files/fra_net/2429/2_C_Operations_and_Service_Plan_Summary.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> Also planned along the Phase&nbsp;1 route are three light maintenance facilities for routine train inspections and cleaning, with locations in the Bay Area, Central Valley and greater Los Angeles, as well as four [[maintenance of way]] facilities spaced throughout the route.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/about/maintenancefacilities/|title=High-Speed Rail Maintenance Facilities|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030450/https://hsr.ca.gov/about/maintenancefacilities/|url-status=live}}</ref> The exact siting for these facilities has yet to be determined. As of 2019, both Fresno and Kern Counties had expressed interest in hosting the heavy maintenance facility.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sjvsun.com/news/fresno/behind-fresnos-pitch-for-the-hsr-maintenance-yard/|title=Behind Fresno's pitch for the HSR maintenance yard|last=Hostetter|first=George|work=The San Joaquin Valley Sun|date=March 14, 2019|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030449/https://sjvsun.com/news/fresno/behind-fresnos-pitch-for-the-hsr-maintenance-yard/|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Phase&nbsp;2 ===

Phase&nbsp;2 would construct two major extensions to the system. The northern extension would stretch {{convert|115|mi|km}} from Merced to Sacramento, with intermediate stops at [[Modesto, California|Modesto]] and [[Stockton, California|Stockton]]. It would largely parallel the existing ''Gold Runner'' route through the Central Valley.<ref name="CAHSR Phase 1">{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/project-sections/merced-to-sacramento/|title=Merced to Sacramento|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030448/https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/project-sections/merced-to-sacramento/|url-status=live}}</ref> In the south, the system would be extended {{convert|167|mi|km}} from Los Angeles to [[San Diego, California|San Diego]].<ref name="CAHSR Phase 2">{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/project-sections/los-angeles-to-san-diego/|title=Los Angeles to San Diego|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030449/https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/project-sections/los-angeles-to-san-diego/|url-status=live}}</ref> Instead of continuing south from Anaheim, it would split off from the Phase&nbsp;1 route at Los Angeles Union Station and travel east along [[Interstate 10 in California|I-10]] before turning south, following an inland route along [[Interstate 15 in California|I-15]] or [[Interstate 215 (California)|I-215]]. This would enable high-speed trains to serve the [[Inland Empire (California)|Inland Empire]] and inland parts of San Diego County, with stops at [[Ontario International Airport]] and [[Escondido, California|Escondido]]. One or more additional stations may be built, in either [[El Monte, California|El Monte]], [[West Covina, California|West Covina]], [[Pomona, California|Pomona]], [[San Bernardino, California|San Bernardino]], [[Corona, California|Corona]], [[March Air Reserve Base|March ARB]], or [[Murrieta, California|Murrieta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/newsroom/maps/LA_to_San_Diego.pdf|title=Los Angeles to San Diego Section|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=March 13, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313192747/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/newsroom/maps/LA_to_San_Diego.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref>

If the entire Phase&nbsp;2 is completed, it would bring the total length of the high-speed rail system to {{convert|776|mi|km}}.<ref name="2024 Business Plan"/><ref name="CAHSR Phase 1"/><ref name="CAHSR Phase 2"/> Phase&nbsp;2 is still early in the planning stages, and would not be constructed until after the completion of Phase&nbsp;1.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/project-sections/|title=Project Sections|publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]]|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314030449/https://hsr.ca.gov/high-speed-rail-in-california/project-sections/|url-status=live}}</ref>

== Rolling stock ==

=== Train design ===

[[File:CAHSR Corcoran 2-scaled.jpg|thumb|An artistic rendering of a CAHSR high-speed train running in the Central Valley. As the model of trainset to be acquired is not yet known, such renderings are purely illustrative.]]

[[2008 California Proposition 1A|Proposition 1A]] sets an explicit requirement for a sustained operating speed of at least {{convert|200|mph}}. The Authority plans to operate trains at {{convert|220|mph}}; with a conventional 10&nbsp;percent buffer for testing, this requires a top speed of at least {{Convert|242|mph|km/h}}.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sheehan |first1=Tim |title=California takes first step to buy trains for its high-speed rail route. What's the price tag? |url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article280078874.html |access-date=April 4, 2024 |work=[[The Fresno Bee]] |date=October 4, 2023 |language=en |quote=capable of operating at speeds up to 220 mph and testing at up to 242 mph |archive-date=January 5, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240105032621/https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article280078874.html |url-status=live }}</ref>
To minimize project risks, the Authority plans to acquire [[electric multiple units]] (EMUs) of service-proven design, for which there are no domestic rolling stock manufacturers. Many specifications are hence similar to those of trainsets being operated in Europe, such as: a lifespan of at least 30&nbsp;years, the ability to operate two coupled trainsets as a single consist ("double heading"), a capacity of at least 450&nbsp;seats and eight bicycle spots, and a length no longer than about {{Convert|680|ft|m}}. Some requirements reflect American legislation or standards corresponding to the local environment, including full [[Americans with Disabilities Act of 1990|ADA]]-compliance, Tier III [[Federal Railroad Administration|FRA]] safety standards,<ref name="FRA tier iii final rule notice 2018">{{cite web |title=Passenger Equipment Safety Standards; Standards for Alternative Compliance and High-Speed Trainsets |url=https://railroads.dot.gov/regulations-fr/rulemaking/2018-25020 |publisher=Federal Railroad Administration |access-date=March 13, 2024 |date=November 21, 2018 |archive-date=March 13, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313024048/https://railroads.dot.gov/regulations-fr/rulemaking/2018-25020 |url-status=dead }}</ref> earthquake safety systems for safe stopping and exiting, and a floor height of {{Convert|50.5|in|cm}} above the rails to enable level boarding.

