=== Operations and ridership forecast ===

In October 2017, the California High-Speed Rail Authority announced that DB E.C.O. North America, a subsidiary of German national rail operator [[Deutsche Bahn]] (DB), had been chosen as the early train operator.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/high-speed/single-view/view/db-consortium-selected-for-california-high-speed-rail-consultancy-contract.html|title=DB consortium selected for California high speed rail consultancy contract|work=Railway Gazette International|date=October 9, 2017|access-date=October 10, 2017|archive-date=October 14, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171014002931/http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/high-speed/single-view/view/db-consortium-selected-for-california-high-speed-rail-consultancy-contract.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Its main service is consulting the Authority in matters leading up to passenger operations, such as ridership forecasts, service scheduling, and operations cost forecasting.

Ridership estimates for 2040 based on a 2023 forecast would total about 12.2&nbsp;million riders annually for a Silicon Valley to Bakersfield service. For the entire Phase&nbsp;1 system it projected 28.4&nbsp;million riders annually,<ref name="2024 Business Plan"/> more than twice the number of annual passengers on the [[Northeast Corridor]] Amtrak services (12.1&nbsp;million) in 2023.<ref name="amtrak FY2023 ridership">{{cite web |title=Amtrak FY23 Ridership |url=https://media.amtrak.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/Copy-of-FY23-Year-End-Ridership.pdf |publisher=Amtrak |access-date=March 11, 2024 |archive-date=December 1, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231201135517/https://media.amtrak.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/11/Copy-of-FY23-Year-End-Ridership.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

