==== Brightline West and High Desert Corridor====
{{Main|Brightline West|High Desert Corridor}}
[[Brightline West]] (formerly Desert Xpress and XpressWest) is a project that has been planning to build a high-speed rail line from [[Las Vegas|Las Vegas, Nevada]] to [[Victorville, California]], about {{convert|90|mi|km}} northeast of Los Angeles, since 2007. The line is intended to cross the [[Mojave Desert]] using the median of [[Interstate 15 in California|I{{Non breaking hyphen}}15]] for most of its length. The separate High Desert Corridor rail line has been proposed from Victorville to Palmdale, extending the Las Vegas line to connect with CAHSR and Metrolink. This project is managed by the High Desert Corridor Joint Powers Agency (HDC JPA).<ref name="HDCJPA prelim engineering grant"/> The [[High Desert Corridor]] is in a preliminary planning and project development stage with construction currently being unfunded.<ref name="HDCJPA prelim engineering grant">{{cite web |title=High-Speed Rail Corridor Project Awarded $8M Grant |date=December 14, 2023 |url=https://highdesertcorridor.org/high-speed-rail-corridor-project-awarded-8m-grant/ |publisher=High Desert Corridor Joint Powers Agency (HDC JPA) |access-date=March 11, 2024 |archive-date=March 19, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240319222837/https://highdesertcorridor.org/high-speed-rail-corridor-project-awarded-8m-grant/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The HDC JPA signed two labor agreements in July 2024.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Schlepp |first=Travis |date=July 9, 2024 |title=Plan to connect California's 2 high-speed rail projects moves forward |url=https://ktla.com/news/california/plan-to-connect-californias-2-high-speed-rail-projects-moves-forward/ |work=KTLA 5 |archive-date=July 10, 2024 |access-date=July 10, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240710032847/https://ktla.com/news/california/plan-to-connect-californias-2-high-speed-rail-projects-moves-forward/ |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Wright |first=Jarah |date=2024-07-10 |title=Another high-speed rail project would connect Las Vegas to additional California stops |url=https://www.ktnv.com/news/another-high-speed-rail-project-would-connect-las-vegas-to-additional-california-stops |access-date=2024-07-14 |website=Channel 13 Las Vegas News KTNV |language=en}}</ref>

After Brightline took over the project in 2018, a separate extension was proposed to run from Victorville and terminate in [[Rancho Cucamonga, California]], where it would connect with Metrolink but not CAHSR. In December 2023, the award of $3&nbsp;billion in federal funding via the [[Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act]], concurrent with the $3.1&nbsp;billion funding for CAHSR, enabled the project to advance.<ref name="nbc federal grants california">{{cite news |title=Feds grant $6 billion for high-speed rail projects |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/feds-grant-6-billion-high-speed-rail-projects-rcna128508 |last=Gagliardi|first=Mike |publisher=NBC News |date=December 9, 2023 |access-date=March 11, 2024 |archive-date=March 11, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240311141311/https://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/feds-grant-6-billion-high-speed-rail-projects-rcna128508 |url-status=live }}</ref> Construction of the Las Vegas to Rancho Cucamonga route began in 2024 and is projected to take approximately four years to construct.<ref name="nevada dot brightline">{{cite web |title=Brightline West High Speed Rail Project |url=https://www.dot.nv.gov/projects-programs/transportation-projects/brightline-west-high-speed-rail-project |publisher=Nevada Department of Transport |access-date=November 24, 2024 |archive-date=October 9, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20241009053148/https://www.dot.nv.gov/projects-programs/transportation-projects/brightline-west-high-speed-rail-project |url-status=live }}</ref>

==== Valley Rail ====

Valley Rail is a program to jointly improve rail service on the [[Altamont Corridor Express]] (ACE) and the Amtrak [[Gold Runner]] for the Central Valley, Sacramento, and the Bay Area. When the IOS goes into operation, the Amtrak Gold Runner segment currently overlapping with the IOS (Merced to Bakersfield) will be discontinued and replaced by CAHSR service. Passengers will be able to transfer at the future [[Merced station (California High-Speed Rail)|Merced Multi-Modal Transit Station]], the northern terminus of the IOS.<ref name="SJJPA 2023 business plan">{{cite web |title=2023 SJJPA Business Plant |url=https://cdn.sjjpa.com/wp-content/uploads/DRAFT-2023-SJJPA-Business-Plan-Update_Public-Review-Draft-1.pdf |publisher=San Joaquins Joint Powers Authority |access-date=March 11, 2024 |archive-date=March 31, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230331224411/https://cdn.sjjpa.com/wp-content/uploads/DRAFT-2023-SJJPA-Business-Plan-Update_Public-Review-Draft-1.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> The remaining service will be expanded under the Valley Rail project, providing passengers with continuing transportation north and west to the Bay Area and north towards/to Sacramento. Valley Rail is currently in implementation and has an estimated completion date of 2030.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marybet |first1=Luczak |title=Transit Briefs: ACE, Amtrak, BART, Brightline West |url=https://www.railwayage.com/passenger/transit-briefs-ace-amtrak-bart-brightline-west/ |access-date=April 6, 2024 |work=[[Railway Age]] |date=March 13, 2023 |quote=ACE's new timeline, it reported, means Manteca, Modesto and Ceres would see stations by late 2026, with Ripton and north Lathrop coming on line in late 2027, Turlock in 2029, and Livingston and Merced in 2030 |archive-date=April 6, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240406001700/https://www.railwayage.com/passenger/transit-briefs-ace-amtrak-bart-brightline-west/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The ACEforward project is further proposed to improve service in the ACE corridor.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.recordnet.com/story/news/2013/08/04/ace-looks-to-expand-speed/44385643007/|title=ACE looks to expand, speed up service|work=Stockton Record|date=August 4, 2013|last=Johnson|first=Zachary K.|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=March 13, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313171415/https://www.recordnet.com/story/news/2013/08/04/ace-looks-to-expand-speed/44385643007/|url-status=live}}</ref>

==== Cross Valley Corridor ====

{{main|Cross Valley Corridor}}

The Cross Valley Corridor (CVC) is a proposed transit line connecting [[Naval Air Station Lemoore]] and the cities [[Hanford, California|Hanford]], [[Visalia, California|Visalia]], and [[Porterville, California|Porterville]] with the future [[Kings–Tulare Regional Station|Kings-Tulare high-speed rail station]]. Its route runs east–west for a total of about {{convert|80|mi|km|adj=on}}, perpendicular to the high-speed rail alignment and mostly along existing rail tracks. During a first phase of up to ten years within opening of the IOS, the CVC will be implemented as a coordinated bus service by local transit agencies. In later phases, the Corridor is proposed to operate as passenger rail.<ref name="TCAG cross valley corridor plan">{{cite web |title=Cross Valley Corridor Plan |url=https://tularecog.org/tcag/planning/transit-planning/transit-plans/cross-valley-corridor-plan/cross-valley-corridor-plan/ |publisher=Tulare County Association of Governments |access-date=March 11, 2024 |archive-date=March 11, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240311192816/https://tularecog.org/tcag/planning/transit-planning/transit-plans/cross-valley-corridor-plan/cross-valley-corridor-plan/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The plans to activate the rail line are currently unfunded.

== Finances and cost estimates ==

=== Overview of project finances ===

The 2008 California voter approval required the project to be financed with matching funds from other sources, including private and federal.<ref>{{cite web |title=Official Voter Information Guide • California General Election, Tuesday, November 4, 2008 |url=https://vig.cdn.sos.ca.gov/2008/general/pdf-guide/suppl-complete-guide.pdf#prop1a |publisher=Secretary of State (California) |access-date=19 March 2024 |date=18 September 2008 |quote=bond funds may be used to provide only up to one-half of the total cost of construction of each corridor or segment of a corridor. The measure requires the authority to seek private and other public funds to cover the remaining costs}}</ref>  The government of Japan offered long-term, low-interest financing if California employed [[Shinkansen]] bullet-train technology.<ref>{{cite news |title=Japan readies loans for California high-speed train |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/japan-california-rail-idUSTOE68D05G20100914/ |access-date=11 June 2024 |work=[[Reuters]] |date=14 September 2010}}</ref>

The project is now financed mainly by the state of California, supplemented by federal grants.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nagourney |first1=Adam |title=A $100 Billion Train: The Future of California or a Boondoggle? |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/30/us/california-high-speed-rail.html |access-date=March 22, 2024 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=July 30, 2018 |language=en |quote=“At the moment, 100 percent of the cost is going to be absorbed by the taxpayers.” |archive-date=March 22, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240322175259/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/30/us/california-high-speed-rail.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=California bullet train costs soar to $77 billion, opening delayed |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/09/california-bullet-train-costs-soar-to-77-billion-opening-delayed.html |access-date=March 22, 2024 |publisher=[[CNBC]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=March 9, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180312155112/https://www.cnbc.com/2018/03/09/california-bullet-train-costs-soar-to-77-billion-opening-delayed.html |archive-date=March 12, 2018 |quote=Predicted private investment has not come in either}}</ref> By the end of 2023, the share of committed funding borne by the state was 76&nbsp;percent. The Authority has only one source of persistent cash flow: an annual $1 billion dollars from California [[cap-and-trade]] auctions set to expire in 2045.<ref name="2025 SacBee cap-and-trade extension" /> Before 2026, cap-and-trade funding was a fixed share of revenue.<ref name="SFC324">{{cite news |last1=Cano |first1=Ricardo |title=California's high-speed rail needs $100 billion to finish — scrapping the project is a possibility |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/ca-high-speed-rail-100-billion-18979091.php |access-date=April 3, 2024 |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=March 16, 2024 |quote=Its sole source of ongoing funds, from the state's cap-and-trade program, expires in 2030 […] the project remains about $7 billion short of the cost to complete the initial segment from Merced to Bakersfield |archive-date=April 3, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240403185329/https://www.sfchronicle.com/bayarea/article/ca-high-speed-rail-100-billion-18979091.php |url-status=live }}</ref> All other funding had been granted as a fixed nominal sum. This implies that if expenditures are delayed, funding does not increase to offset inflation. Headline numbers for cost estimates also depend on an assumed schedule due to inflation; compared to initial funding in Q4 2008, by Q4 2023 the national price level had increased by 39.1&nbsp;percent.{{efn|From St. Louis FED [https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/GDPDEF/ FRED Economic Data]: 123.273/88.613 equals 1.391}}

By the end of 2023, the Authority had been granted funding of $22.9&nbsp;billion and expended $11.2&nbsp;billion. To bring the IOS into revenue service (including trainsets, stations, and maintenance facilities) along with ongoing project development for Phase&nbsp;1 and statewide connectivity programs (blended corridor investments, such as the [[Caltrain Modernization Program|Caltrain electrification]]), it estimates nominal expenditures at around $28.5–$35.3&nbsp;billion, adjusted for schedule. Except for environmental clearance and investments into the blended corridors, no funding had been obtained for engineering and construction of segments outside the IOS.
