=== Funding history ===

[[2008 California Proposition 1A|Proposition&nbsp;1A]], a 2008 state-wide ballot was the authorization by voters for the CAHSR project itself and for the sale of $9.95&nbsp;billion in state bonds, to be made available to the Authority.<ref name="Wired prop1a passed">{{cite magazine |last=Demerjian |first=Dave |date=November 5, 2008 |title=Full Steam Ahead for California's High-Speed Rail |url=https://www.wired.com/2008/11/california-vote-2/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240319153953/https://www.wired.com/2008/11/california-vote-2/ |archive-date=March 19, 2024 |access-date=March 14, 2024 |magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]}}</ref> Out of this sum, $950&nbsp;million were earmarked for other passenger rail services, such as the [[Caltrain Modernization Program|Caltrain Electrification]], to improve connection to the future high-speed rail system.<ref>{{cite web |title=2008 Proposition 1 High Speed Rail Bonds |url=https://repository.uclawsf.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2280&context=ca_ballot_props |publisher=UC Hastings Scholarship Repository |access-date=March 14, 2024 |date=2008 |archive-date=March 14, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314222229/https://repository.uclawsf.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=2280&context=ca_ballot_props |url-status=live }}</ref> Formally, bond proceeds have to be appropriated to the Authority in the California state budget. By the end of 2023, $8.516 out of $9.95&nbsp;billion had been appropriated.<ref name="CHSRA f&a capital outlay Feb 2024" />

The second major funding infusion was a combination of federal grants in 2009, financed mainly under the [[American Recovery and Reinvestment Act]] (ARRA) for a total of $3.5&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mtc.ca.gov/news/obama-administration-invests-235-billion-high-speed-rail-stimulus-funding-california|title=Obama Administration Invests $2.35 Billion in High-Speed Rail Stimulus Funding in California|publisher=Metropolitan Transportation Commission|date=January 28, 2010|access-date=March 10, 2024|archive-date=March 10, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240310230117/https://mtc.ca.gov/news/obama-administration-invests-235-billion-high-speed-rail-stimulus-funding-california|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/02/19/dept-of-transportation-wants-high-speed-rail-billions-back/|title=Trump Administration threatens to reclaim $929 million in California's high speed rail funds|work=[[The Mercury News]]|date=February 19, 2019|last=Baldassari|first=Erin|access-date=March 11, 2024|archive-date=March 11, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240311174525/https://www.mercurynews.com/2019/02/19/dept-of-transportation-wants-high-speed-rail-billions-back/|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the federal funding agreement entailed a tight schedule, targeting construction start of the Merced-Bakersfield section by 2012 and its completion by 2017. In particular, the Authority had to spend the funds in the Central Valley and expend them by September 2017 for risk of losing them.<ref name="TheWeek 2015 Mar">{{cite news |title=The most expensive public-works project in U.S. history |url=https://theweek.com/articles/540002/most-expensive-publicworks-project-history |access-date=March 16, 2024 |work=The Week |date=February 21, 2015 |archive-date=March 16, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240316204309/https://theweek.com/articles/540002/most-expensive-publicworks-project-history |url-status=live }}</ref> To adhere to the deadline, the Authority signed construction contracts before design, land acquisition, and utility relocations were completed.<ref name="FresnoBee 2023 Mar cost increase arra background">{{cite news |last=Sheehan |first=Tim |title=Changes add to high-speed rail construction costs in Fresno region. Here's how much more |url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/high-speed-rail/article273296540.html |access-date=March 29, 2024 |work=[[The Fresno Bee]] |date=March 19, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230512002650/https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/high-speed-rail/article273296540.html |archive-date=May 12, 2023 |quote=among the key conditions were that the money be spent for construction of the rail route in the central San Joaquin Valley and that the funds be exhausted by September 2017. Rather than forfeit the grants, leaders of the California rail authority acknowledged that they pushed to award construction contracts before most of the pre-construction work typical of major infrastructure projects – including substantial design work, purchasing land for the railroad right of way, and identifying and relocating hundreds of utilities – was not even started before the construction contracts were awarded.}}</ref> This would lead to severe disruptions during construction and delays persisting to date (see {{section link||Setbacks on the IOS}}).

In 2014, the [[California State Legislature]] voted to appropriate $250&nbsp;million in state [[cap-and-trade]] revenue for the Authority, along with 25% of all future revenue until the end of 2030.<ref name="LA Daily News 06-2014 cap and trade funding">{{cite news |title=Long-term money a big boost for California's high-speed rail |url=https://www.dailynews.com/2014/06/16/long-term-money-a-big-boost-for-californias-high-speed-rail/ |access-date=March 16, 2024 |agency=Los Angeles Daily News |date=June 16, 2014 |archive-date=March 16, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240316204317/https://www.dailynews.com/2014/06/16/long-term-money-a-big-boost-for-californias-high-speed-rail/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url = http://lao.ca.gov/LAOEconTax/Article/Detail/64|title = Cap-and-Trade Revenue: Likely Much Higher Than Governor's Budget Assumes|publisher = California Legislative Analyst's Office|access-date = January 14, 2016|archive-date = January 19, 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160119110622/http://lao.ca.gov/LAOEconTax/Article/Detail/64|url-status = live}}</ref> By December 2023, it had received $11.7&nbsp;billion through the cap-and-trade appropriation.<ref name="CHSRA f&a cash management report" /> Unlike all other funding, this is the only persistent income stream for the Authority. With a conservative projection of $750&nbsp;million in annual revenue, the Authority expected this source to yield $5.3&nbsp;billion before expiration. The legislature later extended this funding from 2030 to 2045 with a fixed $1 billion dollars a year for CAHSR.<ref name="2025 SacBee cap-and-trade extension" />

In May 2019, the FRA under the [[First presidency of Donald Trump|Trump-Pence administration]] announced that $929&nbsp;million in funding that were awarded under ARRA/FY10 in 2009 but had not yet been paid out would be withheld and cancelled. The reasons given were that the Authority had not made reasonable progress, and that the State of California under Governor [[Gavin Newsom]] abandoned the original goal of connecting San Francisco with Los Angeles, both being in violation of the federal funding agreement.<ref name="CNBC 2019 trump cancels 919m funding">{{cite news |title=Trump administration pulls $929 million in funding for California high-speed rail |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/16/trump-administration-pulls-california-high-speed-rail-funding.html |last=Daniels |first=Jeff |access-date=March 16, 2024 |publisher=[[CNBC]]|date=May 16, 2019 |archive-date=March 19, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240319132235/https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/16/trump-administration-pulls-california-high-speed-rail-funding.html |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="NPR 2019 trump cancels 929m funding">{{cite news |title=Trump Administration Cancels Nearly $1 Billion In California High-Speed Rail Funding |last=Adler|first=Ben |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/05/16/724145472/trump-administration-cancels-nearly-1-billion-in-california-high-speed-rail-fund |access-date=March 16, 2024 |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=May 16, 2019 |archive-date=April 6, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240406061416/https://www.npr.org/2019/05/16/724145472/trump-administration-cancels-nearly-1-billion-in-california-high-speed-rail-fund |url-status=live }}</ref> In June 2021, the [[Presidency of Joe Biden|Biden-Harris Administration]] reinstated the funding.<ref name="Reuters 2021 biden reinstates 929m funding">{{cite news |title=Biden restores $929 mln for California high-speed rail withheld by Trump |last1=Francis |first1=Derek |last2=Singh |first2=Kanishka |last3=Shepardson |first3=David |url=https://www.reuters.com/world/us/biden-administration-restores-929-mln-california-high-speed-rail-2021-06-11/ |access-date=March 16, 2024 |publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=June 11, 2021 |archive-date=March 31, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230331003749/https://www.reuters.com/world/us/biden-administration-restores-929-mln-california-high-speed-rail-2021-06-11/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In September 2023, the Authority obtained a $202&nbsp;million [[Federal Railroad Administration|FRA]] grant to design and construct six grade separations in [[Shafter, California]],<ref name="KTLA 2023 crisi grant">{{cite news |title=California High-Speed Rail gets big boost from Biden Administration |url=https://ktla.com/news/california/california-high-speed-rail-gets-big-boost-from-biden-administration/ |access-date=March 16, 2024 |agency=KTLA |date=September 25, 2023 |archive-date=March 16, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240316221641/https://ktla.com/news/california/california-high-speed-rail-gets-big-boost-from-biden-administration/ |url-status=live }}</ref> part of the southward extension from the initial {{convert|119|mi|km}} towards Bakersfield.
In December 2023, the Biden-Harris administration awarded the CAHSR project $3.1&nbsp;billion of federal funding under another FRA grant program, making it the largest federal commitment since the ARRA-grant in 2009. The same grant also approved $3&nbsp;billion for [[Brightline West]], a similar but privately-run high speed rail project aiming to connect [[Los Angeles]] with [[Las Vegas]].<ref name="Reuters IIJA award 6bn">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-award-3-billion-las-vegas-high-speed-rail-project-2023-12-05/|title=US to award $6.1 billion to Las Vegas, California high-speed rail projects|last=Shepardson|first=David|publisher=[[Reuters]]|date=December 6, 2023|access-date=March 10, 2024|archive-date=December 13, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231213030237/https://www.reuters.com/world/us/us-award-3-billion-las-vegas-high-speed-rail-project-2023-12-05/|url-status=live}}</ref> Both FRA grant programs were funded under the [[Infrastructure Investment and Jobs Act]] (IIJA).

In February 2025, the FRA under Transportation Secretary [[Sean P. Duffy]] of the [[Trump-Vance administration]] ordered a compliance review of the project. Its goal was to determine whether the Authority has been non-compliant with stipulations in agreements between the FRA and the High-Speed Rail Authority, which were accompanying two major federal grants. In June 2025, the FRA released a report on its compliance review, concluding that the Authority has been non-compliant with the grant agreements and thus recommended the termination of those grants, totaling federal obligations of around $4&nbsp;billion. The report claimed that minimal progress has been made on the project, ridership forecasts have been sharply reduced, project deadlines missed, and that there was no viable path for the IOS to be in revenue service by 2033 given a $7&nbsp;billion funding shortfall just for that segment. In its formal response, the Authority rejected the validity of the findings such as on minimal progress, citing 54&nbsp;completed structures and {{convert|60|mi|km}} of completed guideway as well as the completed [[Caltrain electrification]]. The rail authority further contended that the FRA under the Biden-Harris administration executed the $3&nbsp;billion IIJA-grant just eight-months prior when faced with the same factual basis, and that the findings were politically predetermined given a series of prior critical public statements by President Trump and Secretary Duffy.<ref name="2025 nyt fra report repudiation">{{cite news |last1=Vartabedian |first1=Ralph |title=California Offers Spirited Defense of Bullet Train Project |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2025/07/07/us/california-high-speed-rail-funding.html |access-date=17 July 2025 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=7 July 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250708041232/https://www.nytimes.com/2025/07/07/us/california-high-speed-rail-funding.html |archive-date=8 July 2025}}</ref> In April 2025, the administration further cancelled $175&nbsp;million for grade separation, over-crossing and design work. The state of California challenged its legality, calling the decision "illegal".<ref>{{Cite news |date=2025-08-27 |title=Trump administration pulls another $175m from California's high-speed rail |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2025/aug/26/california-high-speed-rail-trump-administration |access-date=2025-09-16 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref>

On July 16, 2025, Acting FRA Administrator [[Drew Feeley]] issued the final decision to terminate two federal grant agreements under FY10 and IIJA, which had carried a remaining federal commitment of $4&nbsp;billion, marking the second attempt of an administration under Trump to cancel federal funding awarded to CAHSR.<ref name="2025 politico fra grant termination">{{cite news |last1=Starcevic |first1=Seb |last2=Nieves |first2=Alex |title=Trump pulls federal funds for California's high-speed rail |url=https://www.politico.com/news/2025/07/16/trump-california-high-speed-rail-00459191 |access-date=17 July 2025 |work=[[Politico]] |date=16 July 2025}}</ref><ref name="2025 la times fra grant termination">{{cite news |last1=Shalby |first1=Colleen |title=Trump administration pulls billions in funding for high-speed rail project; state leaders call decision 'illegal' |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2025-07-16/trump-administration-cancels-funding-for-high-speed-rail-project |access-date=17 July 2025 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=16 July 2025}}</ref> In response, the state of California under Governor [[Gavin Newsom]] filed a lawsuit with the [[United States District Court for the Eastern District of California|U.S. District Court in Sacramento]] in the [[Ninth Circuit]] seeking declaratory and injunctive relief,<ref name="2025 la times grant termination lawsuit">{{cite news |last1=Shalby |first1=Colleen |title=California sues Trump administration over loss of high-speed rail funding |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2025-07-17/california-sues-the-trump-administration-over-loss-of-high-speed-rail-funds |access-date=18 July 2025 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=17 July 2025 |quote=The lawsuit, filed in the U.S. District Court for the Eastern District of California by state Atty. Gen. Rob Bonta, comes one day after the Federal Railroad Administration pulled $4 billion from the project that was intended for construction in the Central Valley. The suit seeks declaratory and injunctive relief and challenges the legality of the decision.}}</ref> alleging that the move from the federal government was a "petty, political retribution, motivated by President Trump’s personal animus".<ref name="2025 wp grant termination lawsuit">{{cite news |last1=Vinall |first1=Frances |title=Trump revokes $4 billion from California high-speed rail project |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2025/07/17/california-high-speed-rail-funding-trump-newsom/ |access-date=18 July 2025 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |date=18 July 2025 |quote=Newsom on Thursday announced that California is suing the Trump administration over the move. The lawsuit alleges the termination of funding is “petty, political retribution, motivated by President Trump’s personal animus,” a news release said.}}</ref><ref name="2025 governor announcement lawsuit">{{cite web |title=California sues to stop Trump's politically motivated attack on high-speed rail |url=https://www.gov.ca.gov/2025/07/17/california-sues-to-stop-trumps-politically-motivated-attack-on-high-speed-rail/ |website=www.gov.ca.gov |date=July 18, 2025 |access-date=18 July 2025}}</ref> In December 2025, the state dropped its lawsuit challenging the funding rescission, and opted to move forward with the project independently, without a federal funding partner.<ref>{{cite news |author1=David Shepardson|title=California drops lawsuit over Trump decision to pull $4 billion in high-speed rail funds|url=https://www.reuters.com/world/us/california-drops-lawsuit-challenging-trump-decision-pull-4-billion-high-speed-2025-12-27/|access-date=31 December 2025|work=[[Reuters]]|date=29 December 2025|quote="Rather than continuing to spend time and money challenging the termination, the state is moving forward without them," the agency said}}</ref>

Meanwhile in September 2025, the California State Legislature voted to extend the state cap-and-trade program from 2030 to 2045, under the rebranded name "cap-and-invest". The previous appropriation from 2014, which saw 25&nbsp;percent of revenue given to high-speed rail, was changed into instead prioritizing $1 billion annually for the project ahead of other uses of the fund.<ref name="2025 SacBee cap-and-trade extension">{{cite news |last1=Wolffe |first1=Kate |last2=Russell |first2=Lia |title=California lawmakers pass climate deal extending cap-and-trade, permitting more drilling |url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/politics-government/capitol-alert/article312084510.html |quote=Democratic lawmakers in California approved a sweeping slate of climate and environmental bills Saturday – a package that would double-down on climate commitments like cap-and-trade and high speed rail [...].|access-date=14 September 2025 |work=[[The Sacramento Bee]] |date=13 September 2025}}</ref> According to the CEO of the high-speed rail authority, this guarantees full funding for the {{convert|171|mi|km|adj=on}} initial operating segment from Merced to Bakerfield.<ref name="2025 LATimes cap-and-trade ext">{{cite news |last1=Shalby |first1=Colleen |title=High-speed rail project slated to receive billions in state funding |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2025-09-12/high-speed-rail-project-slated-to-received-20-billion-in-state-funding |access-date=14 September 2025 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250912103841/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2025-09-12/high-speed-rail-project-slated-to-received-20-billion-in-state-funding |archive-date=12 September 2025 |quote=California’s high-speed rail project is slated to receive $1 billion a year in funding through the state’s cap-and-trade program through 2045 [...] “This funding agreement resolves all identified funding gaps for the Early Operating Segment in the Central Valley and opens the door for meaningful public-private engagement with the program,” Choudri said in a statement.}}</ref> The stable funding guarantee allows the Authority to borrow against that future annual income, so that funding flows do not limit the pace of construction.<ref name="2025 FresnoBee cap-and-trade ext">{{cite news |last1=Galicia |first1=Erik |title=Here's what CA high-speed rail can do with new $1B-a-year promise from state |url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/high-speed-rail/article312083020.html |access-date=14 September 2025 |work=[[The Fresno Bee]] |date=13 September 2025 |quote=California’s High-Speed Rail Authority can consider the project’s initial Central Valley route fully funded [...] [Authority board member Henry Perea said:] “The way money is allocated, money will not be slowing down anything having to do with the completion of the 171 miles.”.}}</ref>

