Although price levels for projects around the world are not directly comparable due to differing topographies, required mitigations measures, and construction prices, high-speed rail projects in the Western hemisphere with similar timelines have also experienced significant cost increases since those were proposed: [[Wendlingen–Ulm high-speed railway|A {{convert|37.1|mi|km|adj=on}} high-speed line in Southern Germany]] that opened in 2022 saw its budget nearly double, from €2.03&nbsp;billion in 2009 to €3.99&nbsp;billion by 2022.<ref name="DB hsr line wendlingen ulm cost">{{cite web |title=Was kostet die Neubaustrecke Wendlingen-Ulm? |url=https://www.bahnprojekt-stuttgart-ulm.de/projekt/finanzierung-und-kosten/nbs-neubaustrecke-wendlingen-ulm/ |publisher=Deutsche Bahn |access-date=March 17, 2024 |archive-date=June 4, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210604095538/https://www.bahnprojekt-stuttgart-ulm.de/projekt/finanzierung-und-kosten/nbs-neubaustrecke-wendlingen-ulm/ |url-status=live }}</ref> [[High Speed 2]], a {{convert|140|mi|km|adj=on}} high-speed line currently under construction in the United Kingdom that will connect [[London]] with [[Birmingham]], has seen its headline cost almost quadruple, from £15.8–17.4&nbsp;billion in 2010<ref name="BBC 11/3/10">{{cite news |url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/8561286.stm |publisher=[[BBC News]] |title=High-speed rail plans announced |date=March 11, 2010 |access-date=November 14, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111026173437/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/8561286.stm |archive-date=October 26, 2011 |url-status=live}}</ref> up to possibly £66&nbsp;billion by January 2024. Construction inflation was cited as the main reason for recent cost increases, with prices for steel, rebar, and concrete having risen by 47, 53, and 48&nbsp;percent respectively during the period since the [[COVID-19 pandemic]].<ref name="Guardian 2024 hs2 cost increase 66bn">{{cite news |title=HS2: true cost of London-Birmingham line is more like £66bn, boss admits |url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2024/jan/10/hs2-cost-of-london-birmingham-line-rise-mps |access-date=March 17, 2024 |agency=[[The Guardian]] |date=January 10, 2024 |archive-date=March 17, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240317030457/https://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2024/jan/10/hs2-cost-of-london-birmingham-line-rise-mps |url-status=live }}</ref>

Similar cost increases have occurred on major California infrastructure projects in the 21st century when faced with similar challenges like the CAHSR project. The [[Eastern span replacement of the San Francisco–Oakland Bay Bridge|Bay Bridge replacement span]] increased from an initial $1&nbsp;billion in 1996{{efn|Original plans for the Bay Bridge, which was damaged in the 1989 [[Loma Prieta earthquake]], were to retrofit the structure for about $250&nbsp;million, but later studies favored constructing a new bridge which was initially budgeted at $1&nbsp;billion in 1996.}} to $6.5&nbsp;billion by 2013, due to initial estimates being made before detailed engineering studies, and due to inflation in the cost of labor and building materials.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-10-13/how-the-cost-of-remaking-the-san-francisco-bay-bridge-soared-to-6-5-billion|title=From $250 Million to $6.5 Billion: The Bay Bridge Cost Overrun|publisher=Bloomberg CityLab|last=Jaffe|first=Eric|date=October 13, 2015|access-date=March 26, 2024|archive-date=March 26, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240326025105/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-10-13/how-the-cost-of-remaking-the-san-francisco-bay-bridge-soared-to-6-5-billion|url-status=live}}</ref> The cost of widening a {{convert|10|mi|km|adj=on}} section of [[Interstate 405 in California|I-405]] in [[Sepulveda Pass]] rose from $1&nbsp;billion in 2010 to $1.6&nbsp;billion in 2016, due to "repeated changes to the project's design and failure to identify and relocate utilities."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-405-freeway-settlement-20161128-story.html|title='Lessons learned': Metro will pay nearly $300 million more to company that widened the 405 Freeway|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|last=Nelson|first=Laura J.|date=November 28, 2016|access-date=March 26, 2024|archive-date=March 23, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240323022033/https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-405-freeway-settlement-20161128-story.html|url-status=live}}</ref> The cost of the planned {{convert|6|mi|km|adj=on}} long third phase of the [[Silicon Valley BART extension]] rose from $4.7&nbsp;billion in 2014 to $12.2&nbsp;billion in 2024, due to years of delays and inflation,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2024/02/01/over-12-2b-chief-of-bart-san-jose-says-theres-a-chance-feds-top-vtas-estimate/|title=Even more than $12.2 billion? Chief of BART San Jose says feds could raise extension's estimated cost yet again|last=Greschler|first=Gabriel|work=[[The Mercury News]]|date=February 1, 2024|access-date=March 26, 2024|archive-date=March 23, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240323022034/https://www.mercurynews.com/2024/02/01/over-12-2b-chief-of-bart-san-jose-says-theres-a-chance-feds-top-vtas-estimate/|url-status=live}}</ref> and to design changes following complaints from property owners along the route.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2023/10/13/opinion-badly-bungled-bart-extension-to-san-jose-could-still-be-fixed/|title=Opinion: Badly bungled BART extension to San Jose could still be fixed|work=[[The Mercury News]]|last=Cauthen|first=Gerald|date=October 13, 2023|access-date=March 26, 2024|archive-date=March 27, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240327175447/https://www.mercurynews.com/2023/10/13/opinion-badly-bungled-bart-extension-to-san-jose-could-still-be-fixed/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In 2023, the Authority published a major cost revision for putting the IOS into revenue service, significantly increasing estimates from $23.4&nbsp;billion in its 2022 business plan to a range of $26.2&ndash;33&nbsp;billion, depending on the degree of confidence. Including past and future expenses outside the IOS, total expenditure of the California High-Speed Rail Authority would increase from $25.7&nbsp;billion to a range of $28.5&ndash;35.3&nbsp;billion.<ref name="CHSRA 2023 project update report table costs">{{cite web |title=2023 Project Update Report |url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/2023-Project-Update-Report-FINAL-022823.pdf |publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]] |access-date=March 22, 2024 |pages=55 |archive-date=March 2, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230302003728/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/2023-Project-Update-Report-FINAL-022823.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> This increase of potentially up to $9.7&nbsp;billion, or 37&nbsp;percent, was explained with the following major factors: $2.1&nbsp;billion, or 21&nbsp;percent of the increase, were attributable to delays in schedule combined with inflation;{{efn|General price increases in the construction sector significantly outpaced consumer price inflation since Covid.}} $3.9&nbsp;billion, or 40&nbsp;percent of the increase, were supposedly due to changes in scope, such as building stations in downtown Merced and Bakersfield upon stakeholder agreement, rather than stopping trains further outside the city centers; and the remaining $3.7&nbsp;billion, or 39&nbsp;percent of the increase, were added as risk contingencies for the higher risk scenario, along with other unspecified elements related to the first two factors.<ref name="CalMatters 2023 March cost increase">{{cite news |last=Vartabedian |first=Ralph |title=New cost estimate for high-speed rail puts California bullet train $100 billion in the red |url=https://calmatters.org/economy/2023/03/california-high-speed-rail/ |work=CalMatters |date=March 7, 2023 |access-date=March 22, 2024 |quote=The roughly $10 billion cost increase on the Merced to Bakersfield line includes $3.9 billion mostly for the decisions to have elevated stations and track realignments in Merced and Bakersfield; $2.1 billion for higher inflation; and $3.7 billion in contingency or reserves for future cost increases. |archive-date=April 4, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240404115836/https://calmatters.org/economy/2023/03/california-high-speed-rail/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

