}}

The high-speed rail alignment shares substantial parts of its corridor with existing freight railroads. Construction activity that affects them are subject to their approval. These third-party hold-ups can cause disruptions to Authority contractors' work sequence, which are exacerbated by any Authority-initiated design changes. For example, the construction of a road underpass in downtown Fresno required also building a bridge for existing [[Union Pacific]] tracks and their temporary relocation ("shoo-fly"). According to CHSRA officials, it took nine iterations of design reviews to obtain approval, with each step taking about 45&nbsp;days.<ref name="FresnoBee 2024 apr fresno road closures">{{cite news |last=Sheehan |first=Tim |title=Lengthy road closures for high-speed rail worry Fresno mayor: 'I stuck my neck out' |url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/high-speed-rail/article286927945.html |access-date=April 12, 2024 |work=[[The Fresno Bee]] |date=April 9, 2024 |quote='Just to get the shoo fly done, we had to go through nine iterations of back-and-forth with Union Pacific,' [CHSRA Central Valley regional director] Fernandez said. 'For every plan submittal, they came back with questions, and every submittal took maybe 45 days for them to review it.' |archive-date=April 22, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240422142603/https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/high-speed-rail/article286927945.html |url-status=live }}</ref> Freight railway companies are further able to order construction stops at or near their railroads during peak shipping season in the fourth quarter of each year, thus narrowing the window for construction.<ref name="KTLA5 finish in five years?">{{cite news |last=Schlepp |first=Travis |title=Could the California High-Speed Rail be completed in the next 5 years? |url=https://ktla.com/news/california/could-the-california-high-speed-rail-be-completed-in-the-next-5-years/ |access-date=March 29, 2024 |publisher=KTLA |date=August 17, 2023 |quote=He [Boris Lipkin, the Northern California Regional Director of the California High-Speed Rail Authority] says the Authority faces hundreds and sometimes thousands of different “veto points” during construction, including blackout windows for construction, third parties being affected by the construction, and even competition with Burlington Northern Santa Fe – the nation's largest freight rail company – which has the ability to pause construction during some of the busiest shipping months. |archive-date=November 18, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231118000834/https://ktla.com/news/california/could-the-california-high-speed-rail-be-completed-in-the-next-5-years/ |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="BNSF public projects manual">{{cite web |title=Public Projects Manual |url=http://www.bnsf.com/bnsf-resources/pdf/in-the-community/public-projects-manual-mtm.pdf |publisher=BNSF Railway |access-date=March 29, 2024 |date=June 29, 2018 |page=12 |quote=Proponents should also be mindful that BNSF has the right to shut down all construction activities on and adjacent to BNSF property during the fourth quarter of each year – October 1 to December 26 – to accommodate BNSF's peak holiday shipping season. |archive-date=April 8, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240408202714/http://www.bnsf.com/bnsf-resources/pdf/in-the-community/public-projects-manual-mtm.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="UP oublic projects manual">{{cite web |title=Union Pacific Railroad Public Projects Manual |url=https://www.up.com/cs/groups/public/@uprr/@corprel/documents/up_pdf_nativedocs/pdf_up_public_projects_manual.pdf |publisher=[[Union Pacific Railroad]] |access-date=March 29, 2024 |pages=2–12 |date=July 30, 2021 |quote=Applicants should also be mindful that UP has the right to shut down all construction activities on and adjacent to Railroad Property during the fourth quarter of each year to accommodate UP's peak holiday shipping season. |archive-date=January 14, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240114101243/https://www.up.com/cs/groups/public/@uprr/@corprel/documents/up_pdf_nativedocs/pdf_up_public_projects_manual.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>

In places where the CAHSR alignment runs close to freight rail lines, such as in downtown Fresno for substantial lengths, safety measures are mandated to protect both lines from a derailment in the other. This resulted in a requirement for the Authority to construct costly intrusion protection barriers &ndash; thick walls made out of steel reinforced concrete &ndash; to separate its guideway from freight lines. According to the Authority, a final agreement with the [[Federal Railroad Administration|FRA]] and the affected freight rail companies [[BNSF]] and [[Union Pacific]] on technical specifications for such barriers was reached only in December 2016,<ref name="CHSRA 2020 sep board meeting IPB">{{cite web |title=Intrusion Protection Barriers (IPB) |url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/brdmeetings/2020/brdmtg_090920_Item4_IPB_Board_Presentation.pdf |publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]] |access-date=March 22, 2024 |archive-date=March 22, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240322154646/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/docs/brdmeetings/2020/brdmtg_090920_Item4_IPB_Board_Presentation.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> well after construction contracts had been issued. The Authority is required to pay all costs for intrusion protection barriers, causing 20&nbsp;change orders totaling about 500&nbsp;million dollars in additional costs.<ref name="CalMatters 2023 March cost increase"/>

=== Legal challenges ===

Hanford-based farmers John Tos and Aaron Fukuda, leading a protest group called ''Citizens for California High Speed Rail Accountability'', began a decade-long series of legal challenges alongside the [[Kings County, California|Kings County]] Board of Supervisors against the California High-Speed Rail Authority when they jointly filed a lawsuit in 2011, alleging that the project violated Proposition 1A funding requirements.<ref name="HanfordSentinel 2014 June lawsuit">{{cite news |last=Niveder |first=Seth |title=Rail authority issues sharp response to county lawsuit |access-date=March 26, 2024 |work=[[Hanford Sentinel]] |date=June 7, 2014 |url=https://hanfordsentinel.com/news/local/rail-authority-issues-sharp-response-to-county-lawsuit/article_0eb076c8-edcf-11e3-b2cc-001a4bcf887a.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140609180050/https://hanfordsentinel.com/news/local/rail-authority-issues-sharp-response-to-county-lawsuit/article_0eb076c8-edcf-11e3-b2cc-001a4bcf887a.html |archive-date=June 9, 2014}}</ref> They oppose the rail project because the alignment would run through their fields, requiring them to sell some of their land for construction and causing a lengthy detour to access other parts. According to Fukuda, “it's not about the money, it's about the crops and the land that are our livelihood.” City officials and residents from the nearby city of [[Visalia]] on the other hand were welcoming of the high-speed rail project, seeing it as a much needed economic opportunity.<ref name="MercuryNews 2014 Jan hanford vs visalia">{{cite news |last=Calefati |first=Jessica |title=Tale of two bullet-train cities: Hanford, Visalia spar over $68 billion project |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2014/01/10/tale-of-two-bullet-train-cities-hanford-visalia-spar-over-68-billion-project/ |access-date=March 26, 2024 |work=[[The Mercury News]] |date=January 10, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221205082605/https://www.mercurynews.com/2014/01/10/tale-of-two-bullet-train-cities-hanford-visalia-spar-over-68-billion-project/ |archive-date=December 5, 2022 |quote=In Hanford, two farmers leading a court battle against the project have become local celebrities, and the anti-bullet-train lawn signs they distribute dot yards across town. In Visalia, city leaders envision the train zipping residents to college classes and big-league sporting events in the Bay Area and Los Angeles region. Locals, they predict, also will take the train to work and reduce the valley's staggering jobless rates.}}</ref>

In 2013, the group achieved temporary success, when Sacramento County Superior Court Judge Michael Kinney ruled partially in favor of one of their lawsuits that was trying to block the Authority from accessing bond funds authorized via Prop&nbsp;1A. The Authority's funding plan was deemed flawed due to insufficiently identifying funding needed for construction, thus violating requirements set in the ballot measure. Stuart Flashman, the lawyer who would represent this group in their series of lawsuits against the Authority, stated that “the point of this [lawsuit] was to prevent the state from moving forward and starting construction on a project they couldn't finish”.<ref name="MercuryNews 2014 Jul lawsuit appellate court" />

In 2014, Kings County refused the Authority access to county-owned property, where it intended to drill for soil samples as part of a study on land subsidence. A court ordered the county to grant access, but the dispute nonetheless caused delays in obtaining environmental clearance, which was still outstanding at the time.<ref name="HanfordSentinel 2014 June lawsuit" /> In the same year, seven lawsuits were filed against the Authority by various cities, businesses and associations, stating that its environmental statement finalized in May 2014 violated the [[California Environmental Quality Act]] (CEQA).<ref name="FresnoBee 2014 Dec lawsuit eis ceqa">{{cite news |last=Sheehan |first=Tim |title=High-speed rail agency settles Bakersfield's lawsuit against route |url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/high-speed-rail/article19528590.html |access-date=March 26, 2024 |work=[[The Fresno Bee]] |date=December 19, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200610232039/https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/high-speed-rail/article19528590.html |archive-date=June 10, 2020 |quote=The lawsuit, filed in June by the city in Sacramento County Superior Court, is one of seven challenging the rail agency's environmental-impact report and final route selection for the section of the statewide rail system between the south end of Fresno and downtown Bakersfield. Still pending, however, are six other cases filed by Kern County; Dignity Health, which operates a hospital along the rail route; Coffee Brimhall, a development company with a proposed Bakersfield project site on the route; the First Free Will Baptist Church in Bakersfield; the city of Shafter; and Kings County, Citizens for California High-Speed Rail Accountability and the Kings County Farm Bureau.}}</ref> All these would eventually be dropped or settled, with Kings County being the last one in 2019.<ref name="LA Times 2019 Jun lawsuit kings county settlement">{{cite news |last=Vartabedian |first=Ralph |title=On California's high-speed rail project, combatant Kings County is ready to settle |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-bullet-train-settlement-20190601-story.html |access-date=March 26, 2024 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=June 1, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231210214532/https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-bullet-train-settlement-20190601-story.html |archive-date=December 10, 2023 |quote=Kings County has long rallied resistance to the project, but local officials say they finally want out of the litigation. [...] Under the informal deal, the county will remove itself as a plaintiff in the bond lawsuit and drop its environmental suit in exchange for $11 million, said Doug Verboon, a Kings County supervisor who has recently led negotiations.}}</ref><ref name="FresnoBee 2019 lawsuit ceqa dropped">{{cite news |last=Sheehan |first=Tim |title=Kings County getting $10 million to settle 2014 lawsuit over high-speed rail route |url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article234062312.html |access-date=March 26, 2024 |work=[[The Fresno Bee]] |date=August 15, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200508045929/https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article234062312.html |archive-date=May 8, 2020 |quote=One by one, however, those lawsuits were dropped or settled over the last five years, leaving only the Kings County case.}}</ref> In July 2014, the Third District Court of Appeal reversed the 2013 decision of the Sacramento County Superior Court.<ref name="MercuryNews 2014 Jul lawsuit appellate court">{{cite news |last=Calefati |first=Jessica |title=California high-speed rail project wins big in appellate court ruling |url=https://www.mercurynews.com/2014/07/31/california-high-speed-rail-project-wins-big-in-appellate-court-ruling/ |access-date=March 26, 2024 |work=[[The Mercury News]] |date=July 31, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230424035818/https://www.mercurynews.com/2014/07/31/california-high-speed-rail-project-wins-big-in-appellate-court-ruling/ |archive-date=April 24, 2023 |quote=But in a unanimous decision issued late Thursday afternoon, the 3rd District Court of Appeal's three-judge panel ordered Judge Michael Kinney to vacate his decision.}}</ref><ref name="HanfordSentinel 2014 Aug lawsuit appellate">{{cite news |last=Nidever |first=Seth |title=HSR court rulings rebuff Kings County, but fight continues |url=https://hanfordsentinel.com/news/local/hsr-court-rulings-rebuff-kings-county-but-fight-continues/article_561c24ca-595b-5c21-a128-63381c95b1f4.html |access-date=March 26, 2024 |work=[[Hanford Sentinel]] |date=August 14, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141019232542/https://hanfordsentinel.com/news/local/hsr-court-rulings-rebuff-kings-county-but-fight-continues/article_561c24ca-595b-5c21-a128-63381c95b1f4.html |archive-date=October 19, 2014 |quote=The two reversals came last month. In one decision, the 3rd District Court of Appeal in Sacramento cleared the way for the sale of $8.7 billion in state bonds for the project approved by voters in 2008 as part of Proposition 1A. In another decision, the court overturned the 2013 ruling by Sacramento County Superior Court Judge Michael Kenny that the authority's financing plan violated Prop. 1A's requirement that all the construction money be identified before the first usable segment is built.}}</ref> In 2016, the remaining part of the lawsuit that argued via Prop&nbsp;1A requirements was dismissed.<ref name="SacrmentoBee 2016 Mar lawsuit prop1a funds dismissed">{{cite news |last=Sheehan |first=Tim |title=In major win for high-speed rail, judge rejects claims by Kings County foes of bullet train |url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/local/transportation/article64736672.html |access-date=March 26, 2024 |publisher=The Sacramento Bee |date=March 8, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218202150/https://www.sacbee.com/news/local/transportation/article64736672.html |archive-date=February 18, 2019 |quote=In a major setback to foes of the California high-speed rail project, a Sacramento judge rejected claims by opponents in Kings County that plans for the bullet train system violate state law. Sacramento County Superior Court Judge Michael Kenny, who heard verbal arguments from attorneys Feb. 11, issued the ruling late Friday but the court didn't release it to the public until Tuesday morning.}}</ref><ref name="CBS 2016 Mar lawsuit prop1a funds dismissed">{{cite news |title=Judge Allows California High-Speed Rail Project To Proceed |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/sanfrancisco/news/judge-allows-california-high-speed-rail-project-to-proceed/ |access-date=March 26, 2024 |agency=[[Associated Press]] |publisher=[[CBS News]] |date=March 8, 2016 |quote=A judge has ruled that California's plans for a $64 billion, high-speed rail system do not violate promises made to voters when they approved state financing for the project. The ruling released Tuesday by Sacramento County Superior Court Judge Michael Kenny allows planning and financing of the project to proceed. |archive-date=March 26, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240326040048/https://www.cbsnews.com/sanfrancisco/news/judge-allows-california-high-speed-rail-project-to-proceed/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Kings County Supervisor Doug Verboon, one of the plaintiffs, stated that "it's all about making them accountable, and not being a waste of taxpayer dollars."<ref name="KFSN-TV 2016 Mar lawsuit prop1a funds dismissed">{{cite news |title=Kings County Supervisor talks after judge dismisses HSR lawsuit |url=https://abc30.com/high-speed-rail-kings-county-lawsuit-loss/1237326/ |access-date=March 26, 2024 |publisher=KFSN-TV |date=March 8, 2016 |archive-date=March 26, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240326040533/https://abc30.com/high-speed-rail-kings-county-lawsuit-loss/1237326/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2017, the California Supreme Court ruled in another case that federal regulations of the [[Surface Transportation Board]] do not categorically preempt projects such as CAHSR from compliance with stricter state environmental laws. This decision meant that the Authority is not exempt from having legal injunctions filed against it based on CEQA; these could force a halt to construction while such CEQA claims are being resolved.<ref name="LA Times 2017 Jul ceqa stb state supreme court">{{cite news |last1=Dolan |first1=Maura |last2=Vartabedian |first2=Ralph |title=California's bullet train is likely to face more environmental hurdles after a high court ruling |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-high-speed-rail-court-20170728-story.html |access-date=March 26, 2024 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 31, 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240116004013/https://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-ln-high-speed-rail-court-20170728-story.html |archive-date=January 16, 2024}}</ref><ref name="NatLawReview">{{cite web |last=Hodges |first=Whitney |title=Faceoff with Federal Government Possibly Looming Following California Supreme Court CEQA Ruling; Cal High Speed Rail Project Also Vulnerable |url=https://www.natlawreview.com/article/faceoff-federal-government-possibly-looming-following-california-supreme-court-ceqa |publisher=The National Law Review |access-date=March 26, 2024 |date=August 22, 2017 |archive-date=March 26, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240326133457/https://www.natlawreview.com/article/faceoff-federal-government-possibly-looming-following-california-supreme-court-ceqa |url-status=live }}</ref>

In 2018, Sacramento County Superior Court Judge Richard K. Sueyoshi issued a ruling dismissing another lawsuit by the group. It had asserted that Assembly Bill&nbsp;1889, passed in 2016 to further specify requirements previously laid out in Prop&nbsp;1A, was an unconstitutional modification of a voter-approved act.<ref name="SDUT 2018 Nov lawsuit AB1998 dismissed">{{cite news |last=Vartabedian |first=Ralph |title=Bullet train survives legal challenge as judge tosses lawsuit over bond funds |url=https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-bullet-train-final-decision-20181101-story.html |access-date=March 26, 2024 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=November 1, 2018 |quote=Sacramento County Superior Court Judge Richard K. Sueyoshi issued the final decision after putting out a tentative ruling last week that found a 2016 piece of legislation did not fundamentally alter the project or redefine restrictions contained in the bond act. |archive-date=March 26, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240326040053/https://www.sandiegouniontribune.com/news/california/la-me-bullet-train-final-decision-20181101-story.html |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2021, a state appeals court affirmed the prior ruling.<ref name="LA Times 2021 Nov lawsuit AB1998 appeal dismissed">{{cite news |last=Vartabedian |first=Ralph |title=State appeals court rejects long-standing challenge to California bullet train |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2021-11-30/state-appeals-court-rejects-challenge-to-bullet-train-project |access-date=March 26, 2024 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=November 30, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240301224659/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2021-11-30/state-appeals-court-rejects-challenge-to-bullet-train-project |archive-date=March 1, 2024 |quote=The Tos case alleged that the Legislature violated the state Constitution when in 2016 it enacted Assembly Bill 1889, which rail proponents said merely clarified the intent of the bond act restrictions. The court rejected arguments that the bill violated the Constitution. The meaning of “suitable and ready,” the court said, could be traced to the rail authority's 2012 business plan, which adopted a blended approach to the system.}}</ref> In 2022, the State Supreme Court denied hearing an appeal, ending John Tos' decade-long series of lawsuits.

In February 2022, [[Hollywood Burbank Airport]] sued the Authority over its then upcoming environmental statement for the unfunded Burbank to Los Angeles segment. Those plans called for an underground high-speed rail station connecting to the airport. Airport officials were worried about impacts on their operations and safety during construction, arguing that the report did not analyze these potential impacts and hence violated CEQA. The lawsuit delayed environmental clearance, and if successful could have required a costly new environmental process to determine a different rail alignment.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2022-02-25/hollywood-burbank-airport-files-an-environmental-lawsuit-against-california-bullet-train | title=Hollywood Burbank Airport files environmental lawsuit against California's bullet train |last=Vartabedian |first=Ralph | work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240321100121/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2022-02-25/hollywood-burbank-airport-files-an-environmental-lawsuit-against-california-bullet-train |archive-date= March 21, 2024 | date=February 25, 2022 }}</ref> In November 2023, both parties reached a settlement that included dismissal of the lawsuit and compensation to the airport for its legal expenses.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://ktla.com/news/california/burbank-airport-drops-lawsuit-against-california-high-speed-rail/ | last=Schlepp |first=Travis | title=Burbank Airport drops lawsuit against California High-Speed Rail | publisher=KTLA | date=November 17, 2023 | access-date=February 3, 2024 | archive-date=November 30, 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231130044036/https://ktla.com/news/california/burbank-airport-drops-lawsuit-against-california-high-speed-rail/ | url-status=live }}</ref>

=== Other ===

The Central Valley with its agricultural focus relies on irrigation canals. These are usually dry from March to September, providing the Authority with a time window of six months per year to conduct work on canal relocations or bridging structures.<ref name="FresnoBee 2023 apr flooding cahsr">{{cite news |last=Sheehan |first=Tim |title=California's beleaguered bullet train faces another hurdle: flooding from melting snow |url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/high-speed-rail/article273844110.html |access-date=April 2, 2024 |work=[[The Fresno Bee]] |date=April 1, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230402210555/https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/high-speed-rail/article273844110.html |archive-date=April 2, 2023}}</ref>
In the spring of 2023, the Central Valley around the city of [[Corcoran, California|Corcoran]] was flooded due to unusual amounts of rain and melting snow.<ref name="NPR 2023 may flooding">{{cite news |last1=Rott |first1=Nathan |last2=Harbage |first2=Claire |title=California's epic snowpack is melting. Here's what to expect |url=https://www.npr.org/2023/05/05/1173069933/snowpack-california-2023-flooding-what-to-expect |publisher=[[NPR]] |access-date=April 2, 2024 |date=May 5, 2023 |archive-date=April 2, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240402153416/https://www.npr.org/2023/05/05/1173069933/snowpack-california-2023-flooding-what-to-expect |url-status=live }}</ref> Some major work sites were completely flooded and unreachable, causing work to halt. The structures themselves are designed to withstand 100-year floods. Further delays were caused due to emergency measures to support affected communities: A road that had been dug up to be replaced with an overcrossing was repaved to provide access to cut-off residents.<ref name="FresnoBee 2023 apr flooding cahsr" />

== Political perspectives ==

=== Support ===
Since the project's inception, multiple California governors have supported the project. Jerry Brown stated in 2012: "During the 1930's {{Sic}}, the [[Central Valley Project|Central Valley Water Project]] was called a 'fantastic dream' that 'will not work.' The Master Plan for the Interstate Highway System in 1939 was derided as 'New Deal jitterbug economics... The critics were wrong then and they're wrong now."<ref name="Dayen 2014">{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2014/02/jerry-brown-california-high-speed-train-103266/|title=He Thinks He Can|last=Dayen|first=David|date=February 8, 2014|work=[[Politico]]|access-date=March 16, 2024|archive-date=March 17, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240317171827/https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2014/02/jerry-brown-california-high-speed-train-103266/|url-status=live}}</ref> In a 2022 interview, Arnold Schwarzenegger criticized the "political provincialism" affecting the project, "You look at the world and very rarely is any system very profitable... When we build schools, we don't look like, 'How do we make a big buck out of this whole thing?"<ref name="Cowan 2022"/>

In his February 2019 State of the State address, California Governor [[Gavin Newsom]] said: "Let's be real ... The project, as currently planned, would cost too much and take too long ... Right now, there simply isn't a path to get from Sacramento to San Diego, let alone from San Francisco to L.A. I wish there were."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://ktla.com/news/local-news/gov-newsom-abandons-plan-for-high-speed-train-from-l-a-to-san-francisco-cites-cost/|title=Gov. Newsom Says No 'Path' for High-Speed Train From L.A. to San Francisco, But His Office Says He's Committed to It|last=Pascucci|first=Christine|publisher=KTLA|date=February 12, 2019|access-date=March 16, 2024|archive-date=March 17, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240317171827/https://ktla.com/news/local-news/gov-newsom-abandons-plan-for-high-speed-train-from-l-a-to-san-francisco-cites-cost/|url-status=live}}</ref> While Newsom said he supported completing the IOS between Merced and Bakersfield and continuing planning for the rest of the route, work beyond that scope would be put on hold until funding issues could be resolved. He then stated, "The project can still be achieved... But let's be honest about the trade-offs and let's be honest about the cost."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2019/02/13/gavin-newsom-high-speed-gift-republicans-225028/|title=Gavin Newsom's High-Speed Gift to Republicans|last=Grunwald|first=Michael|date=February 13, 2019|work=[[Politico]]|access-date=March 16, 2024|archive-date=March 16, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240316213235/https://www.politico.com/magazine/story/2019/02/13/gavin-newsom-high-speed-gift-republicans-225028/|url-status=live}}</ref>

[[Ray LaHood]], former [[United States Secretary of Transportation]] and Republican Congressman who oversaw federal grants to CAHSR under the Obama administration, stated that "When California is finished, it will end up being a good investment. People will use it... For politicians to turn a blind eye to what the people want, it's just not right."<ref name="Baig 2024">{{cite news|url=https://calmatters.org/commentary/2024/01/high-speed-rail-central-valley/|title=From 'train to nowhere' to Fresno's dream: What high-speed rail means for the Central Valley|work=Cal Matters|last=Baig|first=Yousef|date=January 9, 2024|access-date=March 16, 2024|archive-date=March 13, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313225708/https://calmatters.org/commentary/2024/01/high-speed-rail-central-valley/|url-status=live}}</ref> Congressman [[Jim Costa]], one of the original authors of Prop&nbsp;1A and who continues to seek project funding, wrote: "High-speed rail is a modern solution to California's transportation needs, and dismissing it as a pipe dream, or as a romantic concept, will only lead to continued congestion on our roads and delays in our skies."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://sjvsun.com/california/high-speed-rail-receives-3-1-billion-federal-grant/|title=High-Speed Rail receives $3.1 billion federal grant|work=The San Joaquin Valley Sun|date=December 6, 2023|last=Gligich|first=Daniel|access-date=March 16, 2024|archive-date=March 17, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240317171827/https://sjvsun.com/california/high-speed-rail-receives-3-1-billion-federal-grant/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.capitolweekly.net/article.php?issueId=x1uh8zbb6q8afq&xid=x1uzxza4c74tim&_adctlid=v%7Cjq2q43wvsl855o%7Cx1wzkesety80ym |title=High speed rail: a viable transportation system for California
|last=Costa|first=Jim|work=Capitol Weekly|date=April 17, 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110209070157/http://www.capitolweekly.net/article.php?issueId=x1uh8zbb6q8afq&xid=x1uzxza4c74tim&_adctlid=v%7Cjq2q43wvsl855o%7Cx1wzkesety80ym|archive-date=February 9, 2011}}</ref>

Other supporters include local governments along the route, business groups, and labor unions. In 2024, Fresno mayor [[Jerry Dyer]] described high-speed rail as "a game-changer for the Valley and for Fresno," while Merced deputy city manager Frank Quintero called it "a major economic catalyst."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/high-speed-rail/article286649055.html|title=Will bullet-train stations benefit Fresno, Valley cities? Expectations grow as plans advance|work=[[The Fresno Bee]]|last=Sheehan|first=Tim|date=March 16, 2024|access-date=March 16, 2024}}</ref> Jeremy Smith, of the State Building and Construction Trades Council, said, "We should not forget that this type of project is exactly what workers in the construction industry need from their government in times of recession, like times we find ourselves in now."<ref name="Gardiner 2020"/> This support has also come from local elected Republicans, highlighting the project's bipartisan appeal in the Central Valley despite political divisions at the state and federal levels.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-02-21 |title=Trump administration announces review of high-speed rail spending in Central California |url=https://abc30.com/post/trump-administration-announces-review-high-speed-rail-spending-central-california/15938998/ |access-date=2025-05-22 |website=ABC30 Fresno |language=en}}</ref>

=== Opposition ===

California Republicans have generally opposed the project. Congressman [[Kevin McCarthy]] (R-[[California's 23rd congressional district|Bakersfield]]), a native of Bakersfield, stated that he would "do whatever I can to ensure that not one dollar of federal funds is directed to this project",<ref name="LA Daily News 06-2014 cap and trade funding" /> a few days before becoming House majority leader. McCarthy has often pushed for redirecting high-speed rail funding to water projects in the Central Valley.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-11-09/congressman-kevin-mccarthy-offers-a-false-choice-between-funding-california-high-speed-rail-or-dams|title=In Dry California, Dams or High-Speed Rail Is a False Choice|publisher=Bloomberg CityLab|last=Bliss|first=Laura|date=November 9, 2015|access-date=March 17, 2024|archive-date=December 2, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221202115811/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-11-09/congressman-kevin-mccarthy-offers-a-false-choice-between-funding-california-high-speed-rail-or-dams|url-status=live}}</ref> In the wake of economic difficulties brought by the [[COVID-19 pandemic]], State Senator [[Brian Dahle]] (R-[[California's 1st senatorial district|Bieber]]) remarked, "The project is way underfunded and we're never going to be able to finish it... Sometimes you've got to cut your losses, and it's time to cut our losses."<ref name="Gardiner 2020"/> [[Vince Fong]] (R-[[California's 32nd State Assembly district|Bakersfield]]) has also been a vocal opponent, stating in 2020, "We need to seriously reevaluate High Speed Rail funding, especially when this state is asking Californians to make real sacrifices," in regard to "[proposed] cuts to education, healthcare programs, and diverting road funds to address our budget deficit."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bakersfield.com/news/fong-fellow-assemblyman-unveil-bill-to-shift-high-speed-rail-funding-to-education/article_1e9181f0-a13c-11ea-9116-dfdb9605d481.html|title=Fong, fellow assemblyman unveil bill to shift high speed rail funding to education|work=[[The Bakersfield Californian]]|date=May 28, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200623052043/https://www.bakersfield.com/news/fong-fellow-assemblyman-unveil-bill-to-shift-high-speed-rail-funding-to-education/article_1e9181f0-a13c-11ea-9116-dfdb9605d481.html|archive-date=June 23, 2020|access-date=March 24, 2024}}</ref>

A number of California Democrats have also expressed doubts about the project. In 2012, State Senator [[Joe Simitian]] (D-[[Palo Alto]]) asked, "Is there additional commitment of federal funds? There is not. Is there additional commitment of private funding? There is not. Is there a dedicated funding source that we can look to in the coming years? There is not."<ref name="huffington6122">{{cite news|author = Judy Lin|title = California High-Speed Rail Funding Approved|url = https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/06/california-high-speed-rail_n_1655437.html|work=[[HuffPost]]|date = July 6, 2012|access-date = September 3, 2012|archive-date = July 11, 2012|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20120711015221/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/07/06/california-high-speed-rail_n_1655437.html?|url-status = live}}</ref> In 2020, [[Toni Atkins]] (D-San Diego) stated, "I want to see high-speed rail move forward only in a way that is responsible and in keeping with what we told the voters we would do."<ref name="Gardiner 2020">{{cite news|url=https://www.governing.com/community/california-bullet-train-quickly-losing-money-and-support.html|title=California Bullet Train Quickly Losing Money and Support|work=Governing|last=Gardiner|first=Dustin|date=June 23, 2020|access-date=March 16, 2024|archive-date=March 17, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240317171828/https://www.governing.com/community/california-bullet-train-quickly-losing-money-and-support.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

Many advocacy groups have also opposed the project or criticized its management and implementation. The libertarian [[Reason Foundation]] wrote in 2008: "It is possible that HSR can serve legitimate public and environmental purposes and be a financial success in California. However, the current CHSRA proposal cannot achieve such objectives," calling attention to issues such as "questionable ridership projections and cost assumptions" and "virtually no objective analysis about risks and uncertainties."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://reason.org/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/1b544eba6f1d5f9e8012a8c36676ea7e.pdf|title=The California High Speed Rail Proposal: A Due Diligence Report|publisher=[[Reason Foundation]]|date=September 2008|access-date=March 16, 2024|archive-date=November 9, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221109003957/https://reason.org/wp-content/uploads/2008/09/1b544eba6f1d5f9e8012a8c36676ea7e.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2015, the Train Riders Association of California described the high-speed rail project as "throwing good money after bad" and argued that upgrading the existing ''Pacific Surfliner'' and ''Gold Runner'' services would provide more benefits per dollar.<ref>{{cite news|title=Spend Billions for Good Intercity Rail Service|last=Setty|first=Michael D.|work=California Rail News|publisher=Train Riders Association of California|year=2023|volume=31|number=1}}</ref>

While the environmentalist organization [[Sierra Club]] initially supported the project, they shifted to opposing it in 2014, arguing that California should prioritize spending on other efforts to fight climate change, as high-speed rail's benefits would take decades to realize.<ref name="Dayen 2014"/> Many agricultural interests along the proposed route have also opposed the project due to its potential impact on farming operations and the use of eminent domain.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wlj.net/top_headlines/ranchers-and-farmers-resist-high-speed-train-in-california/article_09f876a2-0ab9-11e8-88ff-d71f5d77eb0a.html|title=Ranchers and farmers resist high-speed train in California|work=Western Livestock Journal|last=Mendiola|first=Mark|date=February 16, 2018|access-date=March 17, 2024|archive-date=March 17, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240317171827/https://www.wlj.net/top_headlines/ranchers-and-farmers-resist-high-speed-train-in-california/article_09f876a2-0ab9-11e8-88ff-d71f5d77eb0a.html|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://grist.org/business-technology/its-high-speed-rail-vs-farmers-in-california/|title=It's high-speed rail vs. farmers in California|work=Grist|last=Cagle|first=Susie|date=December 28, 2012|access-date=March 17, 2024|archive-date=March 17, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240317171827/https://grist.org/business-technology/its-high-speed-rail-vs-farmers-in-california/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In February 2025, President [[Donald Trump]] stated he would investigate California's High-Speed Rail Authority, suggesting possible issues in its management and oversight. In response, state officials dismissed his comments as unhelpful, labeling them as 'noise'.<ref>{{cite web |last=Shalby |first=Colleen |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2025-02-05/trump-says-hell-investigate-californias-high-speed-rail-authority-calls-comments-noise |title=Trump says he'll investigate California's high-speed rail; authority calls comments 'noise' |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=5 February 2025 }}</ref>

=== Legislative oversight ===

In 2011 the [[California Legislative Analyst's Office]] (LAO) published a report regarding management issues with the project, citing that plans to obtain future funding were inadequate and were a risk to the project's future viability.<ref name="LAO201105102"/> The LAO recommended that the state seek flexibility with the use of federal funds, most of which was required to be used on the Merced–Bakersfield segment, and recommended the state pursue other corridors in the Bay Area and Los Angeles that could provide more immediate benefits. They also criticized the Authority's heavy reliance on private consultants, which increased costs and complicated management.<ref name="LAO201105102">{{cite web|title = High-Speed Rail Is at a Critical Juncture|url = http://www.lao.ca.gov/reports/2011/trns/high_speed_rail/high_speed_rail_051011.aspx|publisher = California Legislative Analyst's Office|access-date = March 15, 2024|archive-date = September 20, 2023|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20230920065034/https://lao.ca.gov/reports/2011/trns/high_speed_rail/high_speed_rail_051011.aspx|url-status = live}}</ref>

As part of its 2012 funding package, Senate Bill&nbsp;1029 required the California High-Speed Rail Authority to submit biennial reports to the Legislature detailing the project's financial status, construction progress, and operational plans. The mandate was intended to increase legislative oversight and ensure greater accountability in the project's long-term planning and spending.<ref>{{Cite web |title=SB 1029 Senate Bill – CHAPTERED |url=http://www.leginfo.ca.gov/pub/11-12/bill/sen/sb_1001-1050/sb_1029_bill_20120718_chaptered.html |access-date=2025-05-22 |website=www.leginfo.ca.gov}}</ref>

In 2012, the California High-Speed Rail Peer Review Group – an independent panel established by the California Legislature to provide oversight of the high-speed rail project – advised the state not to sell bonds funding the project unless funding issues were addressed. The group wrote that continuing the high-speed rail project without a solid plan to secure future funding represented a financial risk to California.<ref name="cbs2">{{Cite news|last=Buchanan|first=Wyatt|date=January 4, 2012|title=High-speed rail shouldn't be funded, report says|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2012/01/03/BAKF1MKFOG.DTL&tsp=1|access-date=January 4, 2012|archive-date=January 4, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120104043325/http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2012/01/03/BAKF1MKFOG.DTL&tsp=1|url-status=dead}}</ref> The peer review group published an updated analysis in 2022, noting that the project had made significant progress on environmental clearance and addressed many of its management issues; however, "overall project funding remains inadequate and unstable making effective management extremely difficult".<ref name="Peer Review Group 2022"/> It called future cost estimates into question as those sections had not yet been bid on, and that the Authority lacked contract management experiences with key portions of those sections (such as tunneling).<ref name="Peer Review Group 2022">{{cite web |publisher=California High-Speed Rail Peer Review Group |title=April 2022 Report |url=https://www.cahsrprg.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/15/2022/05/Final-2022-BP.pdf |access-date=March 15, 2024 |archive-date=March 19, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240319222836/https://www.cahsrprg.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/15/2022/05/Final-2022-BP.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>  The peer group said the target two hour 40&nbsp;min trip time will not be achieved.<ref name=slow>{{cite news |author-first1=Colleen|author-last1=Shalby |title=High-speed rail financial crisis could get worse under Trump |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2024-12-18/high-speed-rail-financial-crisis-could-get-worse-under-trump |access-date=24 December 2024 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=18 December 2024 |quote=The peer group has pointed out that not only has the project tripled in cost from what was originally proposed, it will take significantly more time to finish, won't meet trip times}}</ref>

In 2022, in order to improve legislative oversight, Governor Newsom and the California legislature agreed to appoint an inspector general to the California High-Speed Rail Authority, a position equipped with its own staffing and endowed with more extensive authorities such as full access to project records and contracts, as well as the ability to issue subpoenas for witnesses and records. However, the inspector general will not be able to directly control spending.<ref name="CalMatters inspector general">{{cite news |last=Vartabedian |first=Ralph |date=July 6, 2022 |title=Will a new oversight position help California's high speed rail plans get on track? |url=https://calmatters.org/economy/2022/07/high-speed-rail-california/ |access-date=March 17, 2024 |work=CalMatters |archive-date=April 6, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240406071624/https://calmatters.org/economy/2022/07/high-speed-rail-california/ |url-status=live }}</ref> In 2023, the governor appointed Benjamin Belnap to the position.<ref name="CHSRA inspector general">{{cite web |title=Office of Inspector General, Benjamin Belnap |url=https://hsr.ca.gov/about/inspector-general/ |publisher=[[California High-Speed Rail Authority]] |access-date=March 17, 2024 |archive-date=March 17, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240317125820/https://hsr.ca.gov/about/inspector-general/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

The California Legislative Analyst's Office has expressed concerns about the California High-Speed Rail Authority's reliance on cap-and-trade revenues as a primary funding source. In a 2023 report, the LAO highlighted that while the cap-and-trade program is authorized through 2030, the future of the program beyond that date remains uncertain.<ref>{{Cite web |last=LEGISLATIVE ANALYST'S OFFICE |date=April 12, 2023 |title=High-Speed Rail 2023 Project Update Report |url=https://lao.ca.gov/handouts/transportation/2023/HSR-Project-Update-032823.pdf |access-date=2025-05-22 |website=lao.ca.gov}}</ref> The LAO recommended that the Legislature consider more stable funding sources to ensure the project's continuation.<ref>{{Cite web |last=LEGISLATIVE ANALYST'S OFFICE |date=April 12, 2023 |title=High-Speed Rail 2023 Project Update Report |url=https://lao.ca.gov/handouts/transportation/2023/HSR-Project-Update-032823.pdf |access-date=2025-05-22 |website=lao.ca.gov}}</ref> Additionally, In 2023 the LAO provided an additional report on cap-and-trade revenues, which highlighted the volatile nature of the Cap and Trade Programs Greenhouse Gas Reduction Fund. The report noted that the Cap and Trade Program is heavily dependent on market health, highlighting that the program generated significantly less revenue in 2020.<ref name="lao.ca.gov">{{Cite web |title=California's Cap-and-Trade Program: Frequently Asked Questions |url=https://lao.ca.gov/Publications/Report/4811 |access-date=2025-05-22 |website=lao.ca.gov}}</ref> The LAO emphasized that such revenue volatility could cause funding shortages for state projects relying on Cap and Trade funds.<ref name="lao.ca.gov"/>

In 2026, the legislature extended cap-and-trade funding for CAHSR from 2030 to 2045 and made funding a fixed $1 billion dollar annually rather than a percentage of revenue, which avoids revenue volatility.<ref name="2025 SacBee cap-and-trade extension" /> 

===Public opinion polls===

Public approval of the project among California residents has remained relatively steady since 2008, when Prop&nbsp;1A passed with 53&nbsp;percent of the vote. In April 2022, UC Berkeley's Institute of Government Studies released a survey of registered voters that found 56&nbsp;percent supporting continuation of the high-speed rail project, even if "its operations only extend from Bakersfield to Merced in the Central Valley by the year 2030 and to the Bay Area by the year 2033", and 35&nbsp;percent remaining opposed.<ref name="2022 UC Berkeley survey">{{cite report | url = https://escholarship.org/uc/item/7sn293xs | title = Release #2022-08: Voters offer a wide range of issues they'd like the state to address | author = Mark DiCamillo | publisher = UC Berkeley Institute of Governmental Studies | year = 2022 | access-date = November 4, 2022 | archive-date = November 3, 2022 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20221103175533/https://escholarship.org/uc/item/7sn293xs | url-status = live }}</ref> Approval varied by political affiliation, with 73&nbsp;percent of Democrats backing the project versus 25% of Republicans.<ref name="2022 UC Berkeley survey"/>

A poll commissioned by [[Newsweek]] in June 2024 confronted eligible voters across the US with the missed 2020 deadline for completion of Phase&nbsp;1 stipulated in Prop&nbsp;1A, as well as with the increase of its initial cost estimate of $33&nbsp;billion to $128&nbsp;billion. Nonetheless, 40&nbsp;percent of respondents deemed the project worthwhile that 33&nbsp;percent who deemed it not worthwhile, with the other 27&nbsp;percent being undecided.<ref name="newsweek 2024 june poll">{{cite news |last1=Bickerton |first1=James |title=California High-Speed Rail Line Gets Boost |url=https://www.newsweek.com/california-high-speed-rail-line-gets-boost-1914694 |access-date=20 June 2024 |work=[[Newsweek]] |date=19 June 2024}}</ref>

A poll commissioned by [[KTLA]] parent company [[Nexstar Media Group|Nexstar]] and conducted by Emerson College Polling was published in February 2025, which found that among a sample of 1,000&nbsp;Californians, 56&nbsp;percent of respondents deemed the high-speed rail project a good use of state funds. The margin of error of the poll was given at three percentage points.<ref name="ktla 2025 emerson survey">{{cite news |last1=Schlepp |first1=Travis |title=Majority of Californians still support High-Speed Rail project, polling shows |url=https://ktla.com/news/california/majority-of-californians-still-support-high-speed-rail-project-polling-shows/ |access-date=19 February 2025 |work=KTLA |date=18 February 2025 |archive-date=February 20, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250220045053/https://ktla.com/news/california/majority-of-californians-still-support-high-speed-rail-project-polling-shows/ |url-status=dead }}</ref>

An older statewide survey, conducted in March 2016 by the [[Public Policy Institute of California]] (PPIC), indicated that 52&nbsp;percent of Californians supported the project, while 63&nbsp;percent of Californians thought the project is either "very important" or "somewhat important" for California's economy and quality of life. Support varied by location, with the San Francisco Bay Area the highest at 63&nbsp;percent, and the lowest in the Orange/San Diego region at 47&nbsp;percent. It also varied by race, with 66&nbsp;percent of Asians, 58&nbsp;percent of Latin Americans, 44&nbsp;percent of Whites, and 42&nbsp;percent of African Americans supporting the project. The survey also concluded that mostly younger Californians supported the project, with a lower support rate as the age increased. Politically, mostly Democrats supported the project with a support rate of 59&nbsp;percent, compared to 29&nbsp;percent of Republicans and 47&nbsp;percent of Independent Californians.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ppic.org/content/pubs/survey/S_316MBS.pdf| title=Californians & Their Government| page=20| publisher=[[Public Policy Institute of California]]| access-date=October 4, 2018| archive-date=November 11, 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201111215405/https://www.ppic.org/content/pubs/survey/S_316MBS.pdf| url-status=live}}</ref>

== Economic, environmental and community debates ==

=== Construction sequencing ===

Concerns have been raised with the plan to start service on only the IOS in the Central Valley. As ''[[The Guardian]]'' wrote in 2022, because the IOS would not reach the major urban centers of the Bay Area and Los Angeles, initial ridership potential could be severely limited.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2022/may/29/california-high-speed-rail-bullet-train|title=Train to nowhere: can California's high-speed rail project ever get back on track?|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Gumbel|first=Andrew|date=May 29, 2022|access-date=March 21, 2024|archive-date=March 18, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240318102058/https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2022/may/29/california-high-speed-rail-bullet-train|url-status=live}}</ref> While previous iterations of the IOS would have connected to at least one of these metro areas, they were scaled back due to lack of funding. While Gavin Newsom has supported completing the line from Merced to Bakersfield, other California lawmakers such as [[Anthony Rendon (politician)|Anthony Rendon]] have argued that the limited funds should be directed to other segments of the line, such as Burbank to Anaheim, which run through more densely populated areas and could see higher initial ridership even without the rest of the system being complete. Rendon described the approach as "not the end of high-speed rail, but a way to save it."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-07-28/california-redirects-funds-high-speed-rail-project|title=In a blow to the bullet train, California might shift billions to L.A. and Bay Area projects|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|last=Vartabedian|first=Ralph|date=July 30, 2019|access-date=March 19, 2024|archive-date=March 19, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240319183840/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2019-07-28/california-redirects-funds-high-speed-rail-project|url-status=live}}</ref> The Authority countered that the Central Valley was the easiest location to start due to the flat terrain, and was the most suitable location for a test track once the first trainsets are delivered. In addition, federal funding granted in 2010–11 was required to be used in the Central Valley segment.<ref name="TheWeek 2015 Mar" /><ref name="FresnoBee 2023 Mar cost increase arra background" />

A 2024 opinion piece published in the ''Times of San Diego'' compared the California project to [[high-speed rail in Indonesia]], which opened its initial section in 2023. The Indonesian rail project only reaches the outskirts of the cities it serves, requiring a long trip on local transit to reach the city centers. Similarly, the California IOS would require a transfer on both ends to reach the Bay Area and Los Angeles. High-speed rail in Indonesia was reporting an operational loss and lower ridership than forecast.<ref name="Matthews 2024">{{cite news|url=https://timesofsandiego.com/opinion/2024/03/15/indonesias-new-whoosh-high-speed-rail-is-cautionary-tale-for-california/|title=Opinion: Indonesia's New 'Whoosh' High Speed Rail Is Cautionary Tale for California|last=Matthews|first=Joe|work=[[Times of San Diego]]|date=March 15, 2024|access-date=March 16, 2024|archive-date=March 15, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240315214726/https://timesofsandiego.com/opinion/2024/03/15/indonesias-new-whoosh-high-speed-rail-is-cautionary-tale-for-california/|url-status=live}}</ref> However, the [[Lowy Institute]] notes that the Indonesian corridor is short (less than half of the California IOS<ref name="Matthews 2024"/>) and already served by frequent rail service while its tickets are twice as expensive, limiting the line's attractiveness to passengers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lowyinstitute.org/the-interpreter/indonesia-high-cost-high-speed-rail|title=Indonesia: The high cost of high-speed rail|publisher=Lowy Institute|last=Anggina|first=Neta Cynara|date=November 30, 2023|access-date=March 16, 2024|archive-date=March 16, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240316173250/https://www.lowyinstitute.org/the-interpreter/indonesia-high-cost-high-speed-rail|url-status=live}}</ref> The ''Los Angeles Times'' wrote: "fares will be one of the most important factors in the decisions that millions of travelers will make when choosing to fly, drive or ride the bullet train."<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/politics/la-me-adv-bullet-fares-20150510-story.html#page=1|title=Doing the math on California's bullet train fares|last1=Vartabedian|first1=Ralph|last2=Weikel|first2=Dan|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 10, 2015|access-date=March 16, 2024|archive-date=March 16, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240316175148/https://www.latimes.com/local/politics/la-me-adv-bullet-fares-20150510-story.html#page=1|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Transport mode and ridership ===

The sections from San Francisco to Gilroy and from Burbank to Anaheim are intended to be operated as "blended" sections,<ref>{{cite news |title=The bullet train's halting journey into downtown San Francisco |url=https://www.kalw.org/show/crosscurrents/2017-02-13/the-bullet-trains-halting-journey-into-downtown-san-francisco#stream/0 |access-date=April 1, 2024 |publisher=[[KALW]] |agency=[[National Public Radio]] |date=February 13, 2017 |quote=the two systems plan to use the same set of tracks, creating a “blended system.” |archive-date=April 1, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240401161011/https://www.kalw.org/show/crosscurrents/2017-02-13/the-bullet-trains-halting-journey-into-downtown-san-francisco#stream/0 |url-status=live }}</ref> in which high-speed trains would share the rail corridor and tracks with slower commuter rail and possibly freight trains, in order to avoid a costly dedicated right-of-way in dense urban areas. This has been the subject of criticism, as it would limit both train speeds and frequencies on the shared corridors. A 2015 report prepared by Eric Eidlin of the U.S Department of Transportation noted that while these were downsides of blended operation (as is the case for [[Intercity Express|high-speed rail in Germany]]), there were also potential benefits, such as improved transit connectivity from sharing existing stations, and reduced noise and environmental impacts.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/281119877|title=Making the Most of High-Speed Rail in California: Lessons from France and Germany|last=Eidlin|first=Eric|year=2015|publisher=German Marshall Fund of the United States|access-date=March 11, 2024|archive-date=February 18, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230218023420/https://www.researchgate.net/publication/281119877_Making_the_Most_of_High-Speed_Rail_in_California_Lessons_from_France_and_Germany|url-status=live}}</ref>

Some Bay Area residents have questioned the safety of allowing high-speed trains to use grade crossings, and pushed for more grade separations along the route.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article235180462.html|title=Bullet train board votes on proposed Valley to San Jose route, amid backlash|last=Sheehan|first=Tim|date=September 18, 2019|work=[[The Fresno Bee]]|access-date=March 11, 2024|archive-date=May 8, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200508061210/https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/article235180462.html|url-status=live}}</ref> City governments such as [[Palo Alto, California|Palo Alto]] have expressed concern that future rail operations would cause traffic congestion at grade crossings, due to the high frequency of combined high-speed rail and Caltrain service.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.paloaltoonline.com/news/2016/05/25/high-speed-rail-launches-study-for-peninsula-segment/|title=High-speed rail launches study for Peninsula segment|work=Palo Alto Online|last=Sheyner|first=Gennady|date=May 25, 2016|access-date=March 11, 2024|archive-date=March 12, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240312042034/https://www.paloaltoonline.com/news/2016/05/25/high-speed-rail-launches-study-for-peninsula-segment/|url-status=live}}</ref>

Because most California cities have less public transit coverage compared to cities abroad served by high-speed rail, some critics have expressed concern that a lack of local transit connectivity may discourage potential riders. Assemblywoman [[Laura Friedman]] asked: "How (do) we turn California car culture into a California culture of transit of all sorts? ... That is the big question — and how does high-speed rail interact with that?"<ref name="Garcia 2021">{{cite news|url=https://calmatters.org/politics/2021/07/california-high-speed-rail-funding/|title=Bullet train budget battle: Should California spend more on urban transit, not high-speed rail?|work=CalMatters|date=July 22, 2021|last=Garcia|first=Marissa|access-date=March 18, 2024|archive-date=March 17, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240317125922/https://calmatters.org/politics/2021/07/california-high-speed-rail-funding/|url-status=live}}</ref> The urban policy think tank SPUR highlighted that to improve the usability of high-speed rail, cities should focus future development and density around stations, integrate them into surrounding communities and public spaces, prevent displacement through [[gentrification]], and provide robust alternatives for station access besides driving.<ref name="SPUR 2022"/> Large investments in public transit are currently underway or planned in the state's major cities, with the Bay Area expanding [[Bay Area Rapid Transit|BART]], commuter rail, light rail and bus rapid transit,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/projects/sf-bay-area-transportation-projects/|title=Bay Area Transportation Project Road Map|work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]]|date=January 26, 2024|last=Cano|first=Ricardo|access-date=March 19, 2024|archive-date=April 15, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240415053148/https://www.sfchronicle.com/projects/sf-bay-area-transportation-projects/|url-status=live}}</ref> while Los Angeles is spending $120&nbsp;billion through Measure M to build out its [[Los Angeles Metro Rail|Metro Rail]] and bus network.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://enotrans.org/article/spotlight-on-measure-m/|title=Spotlight on Measure M|publisher=Eno Center for Transportation|date=July 26, 2019|last=Puentes|first=Robert|access-date=March 19, 2024|archive-date=March 19, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240319200716/https://enotrans.org/article/spotlight-on-measure-m/|url-status=live}}</ref>

In a 2013 analysis, the libertarian Reason Foundation argued that California's ridership projections could be overly optimistic. They noted that California expected 73&nbsp;percent of its total ridership to be captured from existing highway travel, while in Europe, high-speed rail ridership was mostly captured from airlines and conventional rail, with only 11–16&nbsp;percent from highways.<ref name="Reason 2013 Due Diligence Report">{{cite web |url=https://reason.org/wp-content/uploads/files/cahsr_due_dilligence.pdf |title=California High Speed Rail: An Updated Due Diligence Report |publisher=[[Reason Foundation]] |last1=Vranich |first1=Joseph |last2=Cox |first2=Wendell |date=March 2013 |access-date=March 16, 2024 |archive-date=April 10, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230410192717/https://reason.org/wp-content/uploads/files/cahsr_due_dilligence.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref> High-speed rail tends to capture significantly more riders from airlines and conventional rail than from highways, due to the comparable nature of the trips requiring travel to a station or airport.<ref name="Reason 2013 Due Diligence Report"/>

In 2023, about 4.8&nbsp;million passengers flew between the Bay Area and greater Los Angeles,{{efn|Data from the Bureau of Transportation Statistics<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.transtats.bts.gov/ |title=Bureau of Transportation Statistics |publisher=[[U.S. Department of Transportation]] |access-date=March 24, 2024 |archive-date=March 24, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240324180041/https://www.transtats.bts.gov/ |url-status=live }}</ref> for passenger trips between LAX, BUR, ONT, SNA and LGA airports in Southern California, and SFO, OAK and SJC airports in the Bay Area.}} while total 2022 Amtrak ridership in the state was about 6.4&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amtrak.com/content/dam/projects/dotcom/english/public/documents/corporate/statefactsheets/CALIFORNIA22.pdf|title=Amtrak Fact Sheet, Fiscal Year 2022, State of California|publisher=[[Amtrak]]|access-date=March 16, 2024|archive-date=January 27, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240127233903/https://www.amtrak.com/content/dam/projects/dotcom/english/public/documents/corporate/statefactsheets/CALIFORNIA22.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> In comparison, the Authority projected 28.4&nbsp;million high-speed rail riders on Phase&nbsp;1 by 2040.<ref name="2024 Business Plan"/> The Reason Foundation did not account for [[induced demand]], or new trips generated by high-speed rail rather than those replacing existing car, airline and transit trips. A study by the [[Transportation Research Board]] found that among high-speed rail projects worldwide, induced demand accounted for anywhere from 0 to 80&nbsp;percent of total ridership, which represents a major uncertainty in ridership projections.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Induced Travel Demand Modeling for High-Speed Intercity Transportation|last1=Zhang |first1=Dapeng |last2=Luchian |first2=Sara |last3=Ulama |first3=Darryle |journal=Journal of the Transportation Research Board |volume=2673 |issue=3 |date=March 17, 2019 |pages=189–198 |doi=10.1177/0361198119837189}}</ref>

In the early 2000s, forecasters expected California's population to hit 59&nbsp;million by 2040, but updated forecasts in 2023 expect it to remain around 40&nbsp;million, only a slight increase from the population at that time.<ref name="Borenstein 2023"/> With the rate of population growth slowing, particularly after the COVID-19 pandemic, some critics have questioned the need for additional transportation capacity in the state. In 2023, the ''[[Times-Standard]]'' wrote, "...It's time for local and state government officials to recalibrate. Projects that were conceived based on the assumption of an expanding California population will no longer make sense."<ref name="Borenstein 2023">{{cite news|url=https://www.times-standard.com/2023/04/14/borenstein-californias-population-boom-is-over-plan-accordingly/|title=California's population boom is over, plan accordingly|work=The Times-Standard|date=April 14, 2023|access-date=March 19, 2024|archive-date=March 20, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240320004727/https://www.times-standard.com/2023/04/14/borenstein-californias-population-boom-is-over-plan-accordingly/|url-status=live}}</ref> The Authority has revised its Phase&nbsp;1 ridership projections downward, from 38.6&nbsp;million in 2020 to 31.5&nbsp;million in 2023.<ref name="Sheehan April 2023">{{cite news|url=https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/high-speed-rail/article272636534.html|title=How many people will use California's bullet train? Planners lower ridership estimates|last=Sheehan|first=Tim|work=[[The Fresno Bee]]|date=April 17, 2023|access-date=March 19, 2024|archive-date=March 14, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230314025057/https://www.fresnobee.com/news/local/high-speed-rail/article272636534.html|url-status=live}}</ref> The major exception to California population trends is in the Central Valley, which is expected to add up to 5&nbsp;million new residents by 2060. This could significantly increase transportation demand in the state's interior, even with a lack of growth in coastal cities.<ref name="Baig 2024"/>

====Hyperloop====

There was significant press coverage around the [[Hyperloop]] concept first promoted by [[Elon Musk]] in 2013 as an alternative to high-speed rail. Musk proposed that the system of pods carried within vacuum-sealed tubes would be faster than rail and cheaper to construct.<ref name="LA Times Hyperloop 2013">{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-musk-hyperloop-20130813-story.html|title=The Hyperloop: L.A. to S.F. in 30 minutes?|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=August 12, 2013|last1=Green|first1=Catherine|last2=Hennigan|first2=W.J.|last3=Vartabedian|first3=Ralph|access-date=March 11, 2024|archive-date=March 12, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240312042034/https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-musk-hyperloop-20130813-story.html|url-status=live}}</ref> Although the hyperloop concept became publicly popular and numerous media outlets such as ''[[The New York Times]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/18/technology/hyperloop-virgin-vacuum-tubes.html|title=A Real Tube Carrying Dreams of 600-M.P.H. Transit|last=Taub|first=Eric A.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230225001013/https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/18/technology/hyperloop-virgin-vacuum-tubes.html|archive-date=February 25, 2023|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=February 18, 2019|access-date=March 11, 2024}}</ref> and the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''<ref name="LA Times Hyperloop 2013"/> initially published favorable coverage of the concept, physicists questioned the viability of the technology<ref name="McGraw 2022">{{cite news|url=https://www.thebulwark.com/elon-musks-hyperloop-fantasy-ignores-the-laws-of-science-and-politics/|title=Elon Musk's Hyperloop Fantasy Ignores the Laws of Science—And Politics|work=The Bulwark|last=McGraw|first=Daniel|date=June 16, 2022|access-date=March 11, 2024|archive-date=March 12, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240312042037/https://www.thebulwark.com/elon-musks-hyperloop-fantasy-ignores-the-laws-of-science-and-politics/|url-status=live}}</ref> and the projected $6&nbsp;billion cost was criticized as implausibly low.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://archive.nytimes.com/bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/08/12/elon-musk-unveils-plans-for-hyperloop-high-speed-train/|title=Elon Musk Unveils Plans for Hyperloop High-Speed Train|work=[[The New York Times]]|last=Bilton|first=Nick|date=August 12, 2013|access-date=March 11, 2024|archive-date=March 12, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240312042034/https://archive.nytimes.com/bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/08/12/elon-musk-unveils-plans-for-hyperloop-high-speed-train/|url-status=live}}</ref> Hyperloop construction would have encountered the same planning and land-use hurdles faced by high-speed rail.<ref name="McGraw 2022"/> In a 2019 interview, Musk admitted that the Hyperloop was never a serious proposal. Rather, he had promoted it because of his personal distaste for the high-speed rail project.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://time.com/6203815/elon-musk-flaws-billionaire-visions/|title=Elon Musk Is Convinced He's the Future. We Need to Look Beyond Him|magazine=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=August 8, 2022|last=Marx|first=Paris|access-date=March 11, 2024|archive-date=January 27, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240127005924/https://time.com/6203815/elon-musk-flaws-billionaire-visions/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://jalopnik.com/did-musk-propose-hyperloop-to-stop-california-high-spee-1849402460|title=Did Musk Propose Hyperloop to Stop California High-Speed Rail?|work=Jalopnik|date=August 11, 2022|access-date=March 11, 2024|archive-date=August 19, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220819083732/https://jalopnik.com/did-musk-propose-hyperloop-to-stop-california-high-spee-1849402460|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.sfchronicle.com/opinion/openforum/article/elon-musk-hyperloop-rail-17486877.php |title=Sorry, Elon Musk. California's future belongs to high-speed rail |last1=Kunz |first1=Andy |last2=Silk |first2=Ezra |work=[[San Francisco Chronicle]] |date=October 5, 2022 |access-date=March 18, 2024 |archive-date=February 21, 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230221202104/https://www.sfchronicle.com/opinion/openforum/article/elon-musk-hyperloop-rail-17486877.php |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Hyperloop One]], the only company to have built a working prototype, shut down in 2023 after failing to find a buyer for the technology.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/autos-transportation/high-speed-transportation-firm-hyperloop-one-shut-down-bloomberg-news-2023-12-21/ |title=High-speed transportation firm Hyperloop One to shut down |last1=Dasgupta |first1=Aatreyee |last2=Satija |first2=Bhanvi |publisher=[[Reuters]] |date=December 21, 2023 |access-date=March 11, 2024}}</ref>

=== Choice of route ===

[[Image:CAHSR_map_alternate_routes.svg|thumb|The approximate location of alternative routes (blue) considered for California High-Speed Rail, as compared to the currently planned system (black). Brightline West is indicated in orange.]]
A route between the Bay Area and the Central Valley via [[Altamont Pass]] – which was among the corridor options listed in Proposition 1A – has been suggested as an alternative to the Pacheco Pass route. Critics such as the California Rail Foundation<ref name="California Rail Foundation Altamont"/> and Samer Madanat, director of the Institute of Transportation Studies at [[University of California, Berkeley|UC Berkeley]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://engineering.berkeley.edu/news/2009/11/a-reality-check-on-high-speed-rail-for-california/|title=A Reality Check on High-Speed Rail for California|last=Cosgrove|first=Christine|date=November 13, 2009|publisher=University of California, Berkeley|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 13, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313205109/https://engineering.berkeley.edu/news/2009/11/a-reality-check-on-high-speed-rail-for-california/|url-status=live}}</ref> have noted that Altamont would provide a more direct link from the Stockton and Modesto areas to San Francisco, compared to Pacheco which requires a long detour to the south.<ref name="California Rail Foundation Altamont">{{cite web|url=http://calrailfoundation.org/HSR_files/altafinalsm.pdf|title=Why California Must Study the Altamont Pass Alternative In Its High-speed Rail EIR|publisher=California Rail Foundation|access-date=March 13, 2024|archive-date=August 5, 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220805063540/http://calrailfoundation.org/HSR_files/altafinalsm.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://transdef.org/HSR/Altamont_assets/Exhibit_C.pdf|title=Evaluation of an Alignment for the California High-Speed Rail Project Bay Area to Central Valley Segment|publisher=Transportation Solutions Defense and Education Fund|date=April 25, 2010|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 13, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313205111/https://transdef.org/HSR/Altamont_assets/Exhibit_C.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref>

As of 2020, the [[Sierra Club]] also opposed the Pacheco route in favor of Altamont, citing the greater impacts of the former on Coast Range wildlife and its potential to induce [[urban sprawl]] in the countryside surrounding Gilroy.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.mantecabulletin.com/news/local-news/sierra-club-chapter-look-high-speed-altamont-option/|title=Sierra Club Chapter: Look at High Speed Altamont Option|work=[[Manteca Bulletin]]|date=August 28, 2020|last=Wyatt|first=Dennis|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 13, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313205110/https://www.mantecabulletin.com/news/local-news/sierra-club-chapter-look-high-speed-altamont-option/|url-status=live}}</ref> Sprawl has been a general concern since the early planning of the project; a station in [[Los Banos, California|Los Banos]] – which the Pacheco route passes between Gilroy and Merced – was specifically prohibited by Prop 1A as a compromise for the Sierra Club and other environmental groups to endorse the ballot.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.kalw.org/show/crosscurrents/2017-02-13/some-mega-commuters-may-not-reap-the-benefits-of-california-bullet-train|title=Some mega-commuters may not reap the benefits of California bullet train|last=Johnston|first=Angela|publisher=KALW|date=February 13, 2017|access-date=March 27, 2024|archive-date=March 27, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240327170503/https://www.kalw.org/show/crosscurrents/2017-02-13/some-mega-commuters-may-not-reap-the-benefits-of-california-bullet-train|url-status=live}}</ref>

The Authority has intended to build the Pacheco route since 2007,<ref name="Lew 2007">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.wired.com/2007/12/california-high/|title=California High Speed Rail's Route Debate Is Over|magazine=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]]|date=December 22, 2007|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=November 21, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231121015505/https://www.wired.com/2007/12/california-high/|url-status=live}}</ref> and as of 2024 its plans remained unchanged.<ref name="2024 Business Plan"/> Because of its more northerly location, the alternative Altamont route would bypass downtown San Jose and require either a tunnel under [[San Francisco Bay]] or the reconstruction of the [[Dumbarton Rail Bridge]].<ref name="Lew 2007"/> The Altamont route would also pass through more heavily urbanized areas than the Pacheco route, potentially leading to more opposition from property owners.<ref name="Lew 2007"/> Planned upgrades to other existing Northern California rail lines are expected to improve service and increase speeds through Altamont Pass, as well as from Sacramento to the Bay Area.{{efn|As of 2019, planned upgrades to the existing ACE commuter rail route across Altamont Pass would provide a fast and frequent connection from Stockton, Modesto and Merced to the South Bay,{{fact|date=April 2024}} while the [[Dumbarton Rail Corridor]] project plans to restore service (for non-high-speed commuter trains) on the Dumbarton crossing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.samtrans.com/media/5006/download?inline|title=Dumbarton Rail Corridor Project|publisher=San Mateo County Transit District|date=January 2020|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=January 8, 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230108120803/https://www.samtrans.com/media/5006/download?inline|url-status=live}}</ref> The existing Capitol Corridor service between Sacramento, Oakland and San Jose is also planned to be improved with more frequent service and speeds up to {{convert|150|mph}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.capitolcorridor.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/CCJPAVisionPlan_Volume1.pdf|title=Capitol Corridor 2014 Vision Plan Update Final Report|publisher=Capitol Corridor Joint Powers Authority|year=2014|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 13, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313205110/https://www.capitolcorridor.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/12/CCJPAVisionPlan_Volume1.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref>}}

Routing high-speed rail along [[Interstate 5|I-5]], which would have provided a shorter trip between the Bay Area and Southern California but bypassed Fresno and Bakersfield,{{efn|The I-5 route would have included lower speed branch lines to connect the Central Valley cities to the main line.{{fact|date=April 2024}}}} was also discussed in the 2000s. [[SNCF]], the French national high-speed rail operator, proposed an I-5 alignment to the Authority and offered to build it with the help of foreign investment,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-rail-advice-20120709,0,973921,full.story |title=High-speed rail officials rebuffed proposal from French railway |last1=Weikel |first1=Dan |last2=Vartabedian |first2=Ralph |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 9, 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120715031917/https://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-rail-advice-20120709,0,973921,full.story |archive-date=July 15, 2012}}</ref><ref name="nytimes/rail-politics">{{cite news |last1=Vartabedian |first1=Ralph |title=How California's Bullet Train Went Off the Rails |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2022/10/09/us/california-high-speed-rail-politics.html |access-date=October 9, 2022 |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=October 9, 2022 |quote=The company's recommendations for a direct route out of Los Angeles and a focus on moving people between Los Angeles and San Francisco were cast aside, said Dan McNamara, a career project manager for SNCF | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221009102347/https://www.nytimes.com/2022/10/09/us/california-high-speed-rail-politics.html |archive-date=October 9, 2022}}</ref> although in 2009 they also expressed their interest in building the state's official proposed alignment.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thetransportpolitic.com/sncf/California.pdf|title=Executive Summary|publisher=The Transport Politic|author=SNCF|date=September 14, 2009|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 13, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313205109/https://www.thetransportpolitic.com/sncf/California.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref> The Authority turned down SNCF's involvement in 2011, in part due to "Buy America" requirements that mandate transportation projects using federal funds to use domestically produced trains and materials,<ref name="Kim 2023">{{cite news|url=https://www.politico.com/news/2023/05/28/buy-america-high-speed-trains-00097776|title=How 'Buy America' could delay high-speed trains|work=[[Politico]]|date=May 28, 2023|last=Kim|first=Minho|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 13, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313205109/https://www.politico.com/news/2023/05/28/buy-america-high-speed-trains-00097776|url-status=live}}</ref> and due to political considerations as Proposition 1A outlined a route through Fresno and Bakersfield.<ref name="Kim 2023"/><ref name="Prop 1A text"/>

A route from the Central Valley to Southern California through [[Tejon Pass]] (the Grapevine along I-5), which would be shorter than the route through Tehachapi Pass and Palmdale, was initially disconsidered because initial studies expected Tejon would require more tunneling. In 2012, the Authority reopened a study of the Tejon route after it was found that the Palmdale route would need more tunneling than anticipated. The study was canceled after the city of Palmdale threatened to sue, citing that Prop&nbsp;1A specifies a route through there.<ref name="Prop 1A text"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bakersfield.com/news/high-speed-rail-faces-tough-climb-over-tehachapis/article_310bd2f4-54e8-5307-9172-4734c615dfab.html|title=High-speed rail faces tough climb over Tehachapis|last=Cox|first=John|work=[[The Bakersfield Californian]]|date=September 12, 2016|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 13, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313205109/https://www.bakersfield.com/news/high-speed-rail-faces-tough-climb-over-tehachapis/article_310bd2f4-54e8-5307-9172-4734c615dfab.html|url-status=live}}</ref> The owners of [[Tejon Ranch]], which has large land holdings in Tejon Pass, also opposed the Tejon route and pressured the Authority to drop the study.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ocregister.com/2012/02/06/high-speed-rails-coming-battle-powerful-land-owners/|title=High-speed rail's coming battle: Powerful land owners|work=[[The Orange County Register]]|date=February 6, 2012|last=Joseph|first=Brian|access-date=March 12, 2024|archive-date=March 13, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240313205109/https://www.ocregister.com/2012/02/06/high-speed-rails-coming-battle-powerful-land-owners/|url-status=live}}</ref> Although the Tejon route would provide a faster north-south trip, it would miss the opportunity to connect with Brightline West in Palmdale.

In a 2025 project update report to state legislators, the Authority laid out the option of re-sequencing the project such that [[Merced]], which so far had been prioritized as the northern terminus of the initial operating segment (IOS), would be de-prioritized in favor of diverting its limited funding to a faster build-out towards [[Gilroy (California)|Gilroy]], thus connecting to the Bay Area population center. Any such change to the existing prioritization of the IOS would require legislative approval. Within the full Phase&nbsp;1 system, Merced does not directly lie on the mainline that would connect San Francisco with Los Angeles, but instead is the end node of a shorter segment branching off the former.<ref name="2025 CHSRA supplemental PUR">{{cite web |title=2025 Supplemental Project Update Report |url=https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/2025-Project-Update-Report-SUP-FINAL-081925-A11Y.pdf |website=hsr.ca.gov |publisher=[[California High Speed Rail Authority]] |access-date=14 September 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250823141815/https://hsr.ca.gov/wp-content/uploads/2025/08/2025-Project-Update-Report-SUP-FINAL-081925-A11Y.pdf |archive-date=23 August 2025}}</ref> Projected over 40&nbsp;years, the Bay Area connection via Gilroy would result in a $47.5&nbsp;billion operating profit, compared to a $3.8&nbsp;billion loss on just a Merced-to-Bakersfield segment.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://kmph.com/newsletter-daily/new-high-speed-rail-proposal-raises-concerns-about-merceds-role-in-the-project |title=New High-Speed Rail proposal raises concerns about Merced's role in the project |last1=Franco |first1 = Maya |last2= Aikins |first2=Adjoa |date=September 5, 2025 |work=[[KMPH-TV]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://themercedfocus.org/merced-might-be-removed-from-initial-california-bullet-train-route-to-cut-costs-report-suggests/ |title= Merced might be removed from initial California bullet train route to cut costs, report suggests |publisher=The Merced Focus |last=Patton |first=Victor A. |date=August 22, 2025 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250901172229/https://themercedfocus.org/merced-might-be-removed-from-initial-california-bullet-train-route-to-cut-costs-report-suggests/ |archive-date=1 September 2025}}</ref>

=== Construction impact on communities ===

Construction work in the Central Valley has caused disruptions, such as noise and air quality impacts to residents along the route, and road closures at overpass construction sites.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Shalby |first1=Colleen |title=Despite some progress, state's high-speed rail is $100 billion short and many years from reality |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2024-03-21/high-speed-rail |access-date=March 29, 2024 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=March 21, 2024 |quote=In downtown Fresno, for example, a thoroughfare road has been closed for eight years. In Bakersfield, business owners have sought clarity about when they'll have to move, and where they will relocate to, making planning difficult |archive-date=April 3, 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240403161353/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2024-03-21/high-speed-rail |url-status=live }}</ref> The city of [[Wasco, California|Wasco]] raised concerns about neglect of properties purchased by the Authority along the rail alignment, which had become blighted and attracted squatters for several years. In November 2021 the city reached a resolution with the Authority to clean up the site.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cityofwasco.org/305/High-Speed-Rail-Impact-on-Wasco|title=High-Speed Rail Impact on Wasco|publisher=City of Wasco|access-date=March 26, 2024|archive-date=March 24, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240324190849/https://www.cityofwasco.org/305/High-Speed-Rail-Impact-on-Wasco|url-status=live}}</ref> Properties were taken by eminent domain in Fresno, Bakersfield and smaller cities along the route. Assemblyman [[Vince Fong]] (R-Bakersfield) said that "the high-speed rail authority is trying to sugar coat the impacts it is having on communities... It impacts significantly part of Bakersfield that is socioeconomically disadvantaged."<ref>{{cite news |last1=Vartabedian |first1=Ralph |title=Bullet train leaves a trail of grief among the disadvantaged of the San Joaquin Valley |url=https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2021-10-29/california-bullet-train-impacts-disadvantaged-communities-san-joaquin-valley |access-date=November 11, 2021 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=October 29, 2021 |language=en |quote=up and down the San Joaquin Valley, the bullet train is hitting hard at people who are already struggling to survive tough economic conditions in one of the poorest regions in the nation |archive-date=November 11, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211111193609/https://www.latimes.com/california/story/2021-10-29/california-bullet-train-impacts-disadvantaged-communities-san-joaquin-valley |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Valadao sends letter to High-Speed Rail Authority in defense of Wasco |url=https://www.bakersfield.com/news/valadao-sends-letter-to-high-speed-rail-authority-in-defense-of-wasco/article_c4ff16da-98c4-11eb-b73d-33b640e1ae31.html |access-date=November 16, 2021 |work=[[The Bakersfield Californian]] |date=April 8, 2021 |language=en |quote=The construction of the rail has disrupted businesses and homes, worsened air quality, and the abandoned Wasco Farm Labor Housing complex has posed serious health and safety risks |archive-date=November 16, 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211116170758/https://www.bakersfield.com/news/valadao-sends-letter-to-high-speed-rail-authority-in-defense-of-wasco/article_c4ff16da-98c4-11eb-b73d-33b640e1ae31.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

The project has impacted agriculture along its route in the Central Valley, with portions of several large properties being cut off from access, disruption of irrigation systems, and a reduction in the acreage available for farming. While the state is legally required to compensate farmers for financial setbacks and the use of their land, some payments have been significantly delayed, sometimes by up to a year.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-bullet-train-cash-20190610-story.html|title=High-speed rail route took land from farmers. The money they're owed hasn't arrived|last=Vartabedian|first=Ralph|date=June 10, 2019|access-date=March 18, 2024|archive-date=March 18, 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240318191009/https://www.latimes.com/local/california/la-me-bullet-train-cash-20190610-story.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

